<HEAD>Jim And Tammy Bakker Plan To Return To Television On Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> begin broadcasting a new television show from their living room Monday for at least six independent television stations across the nation, according to a published report. <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> and three of his associates were indicted this month on charges of misusing millions of dollars in <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> funds. <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> could not be reached for comment Thursday. The Charlotte Observer in Friday's editions quoted unidentified sources as saying that the live broadcasts from the <ORGANIZATION> Bakkers </ORGANIZATION>' living room near <LOCATION> Pineville </LOCATION> will be carried on stations in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Chico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Toms </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hendersonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, said in a telephone interview Thursday night that the <ORGANIZATION> Bakkers </ORGANIZATION> had been preparing to return to television, but could not confirm when the return would take place. <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> has not had a regular TV show since he resigned from <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> in March 1987 after widely publicized allegations of his 1980 sexual encounter with church secretary <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> and payments to keep her quiet.
