<SECOND>PM-Hated Maverick,0884</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Leader Gives Thatcher Competition as Hate Figure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROMLEY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Other labor leaders shun <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> and he rivals <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> as a hate figure for the left, but many see the maverick union boss as a natural product of the prime minister's age of enterprise. <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> is the polecat of organized labor, particularly since his electricians' union was expelled from the national labor federation, and he appears to enjoy the role. His eyes twinkle as he lauds laws that have emasculated the once-mighty labor movement since Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and her <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> won power in 1979. `` I'm only half-joking when I say we'll be erecting statues to the <ORGANIZATION> Tories </ORGANIZATION> before the end of the century,'' he said. `` Why? Because they will have saved the trade union movement from itself.'' Labor legislation in the Thatcher decade has outlawed sympathy walkouts, forced secret-ballot membership votes before strikes are called and empowered employers to sue unions for damages resulting from illegal strikes. A revolution was wrought in British working practices, and <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>'s 360,000-member Electrical, Electronic, <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plumbing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> joined it. In his office at the union's elegant headquarters, a converted mansion in commuter country 10 miles from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> continues the union-baiting that got him banished from the <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the 9 million-member British labor federation. He is accused of splitting organized labor, making cozy no-strike deals with employers, invading the territory of other unions and, through a 1986 deal with publisher <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> to run his high-technology presses, breaking the power of newspaper production unions. <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, 59, is a sharp contrast and constant provocation to left-wing leaders of old, traditional unions: <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Scargill </PERSON> and his <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mineworkers </ORGANIZATION>, for instance, and the huge <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> with its 1,250,000 members. `` Hard times have been forced upon the unions and the way <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> has tried to solve this is through sweetheart deals with employers,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON>, an official of the transport union. `` A strike is always a weapon of last resort. The question is whether union officials have the right to surrender that resort.'' In September, the <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> expelled <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>'s electricians for refusing to abandon single-union, no-strike deals with a Japanese electronics company in <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION> and a British food chain <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, unrepentant, delivered his credo in a final speech to the federation's annual conference and walked out before the expulsion vote was taken. `` Our members,'' he thundered, `` reveal an enthusiasm for the market system and its values and infuriate the sherry-party revolutionaries with their model resolutions and conference-hall rhetoric.'' He is negotiating a merger with the <ORGANIZATION> Amalgamated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, which has 800,000 members and is the nation's second largest after the transport workers. If that goes through next year, the <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must either take the electricians back in their new form or risk the emergence of a rival federation of the highest-skilled workers. Although <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> is isolated, at least for now, he sees himself as the smart kid on the block, the adapter to modern realities in a bleak time for organized labor. Membership in unions belonging to the <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has declined from nearly 13 million to under 9 million since 1979. Nearly 50 percent of British workers belonged to unions then, but only 35 percent do now. <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>'s background is impeccably working class. He is the son of a paper-mill timekeeper, grew up in a modest home at <LOCATION> Gravesend </LOCATION>, 20 miles east of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, and became an apprentice electrician at 16. He began as a leftist, he said, but moved right. Communists took over the union but were kicked out in a 1962 ballot-rigging scandal and the right has controlled it since. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapple </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>'s Cockney predecessor, was the scourge of the left in the socialist <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which unions founded and finance. <PERSON> Chapple </PERSON>, now a life peer sitting in the non-elected <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lords </ORGANIZATION>, warned his many enemies in the <ORGANIZATION> Tredes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> when he retired four years ago: `` You think I'm right-wing? Wait till you see <PERSON> Eric </PERSON>.'' Experience bore him out. <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> has excoriated the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> for, as he put it, consorting with `` terrorists, lesbians and other queer folk.'' He has pushed single-union deals, with or without no-strike clauses that stipulate binding arbritration. Unions have made more than 30 such arrangements, mainly with Japanese electronic companies _ often after several unions vie to offer managers the most attractive package. <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>'s alliance with <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> revolutionized the newspaper industry in less than two years. When <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> fired 5,000 production workers in January 1986 for striking against new high-tech machinery, <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> and his electricians moved in to run the presses. With the production unions vanquished, the rest of the national newspaper industry quickly followed suit. `` The other unions were demanding jobs for life ... and <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> said, ` Get lost','' <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> said in the interview. `` I do n't see how we could have acted any differently.'' `` These deals are what our members want, and that's what it's all about _ membership. We're operating in a tough environment.''
