<FIRST>r w PM-ChemicalWeapons Bjt   12-30 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Weapons, Bjt,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Trying To Reverse The Trend</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, in one of his last official acts, will undertake an international effort next week in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to roll back the proliferation of chemical weapons technology. He will represent the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at a multinational conference in the French capital that is expected to reaffirm a 1925 protocol banning the use of chemical weapons and to encourage completion of negotiations among 40 nations in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> of a new agreement prohibiting production. Some 20 nations, by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> estimate, either have produced chemical weapons or are capable of manufacturing them. Among them the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> includes <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, whose leader, <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>, is accused by the department of supporting terrorism. <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> `` is one of the more recent ones, and one of the more irresponsible ones'' to reach the edge of production, said a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official who spoke on condition of anonymity. At one time, the civilized world abhorred poison gas. But <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> discovered in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war that chemical weapons were effective against numerically superior Iranian forces. And some Third World countries resent interference with their chemical industries. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> stopped production in 1969, then resumed 17 years later on the grounds the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and other potential adversaries had chemical weapons programs. Currently, chemical components and artillery shells to contain them are being produced but stockpiled separately. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> proposed the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> conference in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> last September. President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said during the election campaign in October that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must take the lead in making sure that nations using chemical and biological weapons are punished. `` The barriers against chemical warfare, breached as we've seen during the Iran-Iraq war, must be repaired and raised even higher,'' he said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> vowed to make nations that use such weapons `` pay a price.'' Realistically, though, the 1925 protocol, to which 130 nations are parties, has no enforcement provisions. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, which denied using the weapons, is one of them. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed a global ban in 1984 while twice casting tie-breaking votes in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to continue financing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production. An aide explained that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> felt that as long as the Soviets produced chemical weapons the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should keep up. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> acknowledged in 1987 possession of chemical weapons, then claimed to have ceased production. A foreign ministry spokesman said 50,000 tons would be stored, the rest destroyed. Officials of the two countries have held nine sessions in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> to plan ways to restrict proliferation. So far, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are the only two countries in the world to admit possessing chemical weapons. But in recent weeks the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has accused <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> of having a chemical weapons plant. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in a recent television interview, said the government has not ruled out a military strike against the plant. The <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> conference is expected to reaffirm the 1925 ban on using the weapons and to urge adoption of a verifiable ban on production, as well, by the 40-nation disarmament conference that meets in February in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. Two other steps may be taken in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>: authorizing the secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to investigate allegations of the use of chemical weapons, and some form of assistance for victims. Nearly all the 159 nations that are members of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> are sending their foreign ministers or ambassadors to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. `` You can expect an enormous turnout,'' said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official, who is involved in preparations for the Jan. 7-11 conference. Whatever declaration emerges, there is no way to enforce it, although sanctions may be discussed. And, the official said, `` there is a great allergy, particularly in the Arab world, to pointing fingers at their capabilities and their emerging capabilities. So that becomes a bit sensitive.'' Assuming the 40 nations in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, which do not include <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, decide to ban the production and possession of chemical weapons, there still will be an enormous problem. `` We recognize that verification is a very complicated problem,'' the official said. `` When you are talking about not producing chemical agents, that raises all kinds of very difficult issues. Any chemical industry which can produce pesticides to kill insects can probably produce chemical agents to kill people. And that's one of the frightening parts of this whole business. They are relatively simple to construct and to make.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Schweid </PERSON> covers diplomacy for The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>.
