<HEAD>A Guru By Any Other Name Would Be Just As Divine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 You can call him <PERSON> Shree </PERSON>. And you can call him <PERSON> Rajneesh </PERSON>. But <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s former self-styled guru of wealth and free love, <PERSON> Bhagwan </PERSON> <PERSON> Shree </PERSON> <PERSON> Rajneesh </PERSON>, says until further notice that you do n't need to call him God. <PERSON> Rajneesh </PERSON> announced Thursday he has dropped the honorific title of <PERSON> Bhagwan </PERSON>, a Hindi word meaning God. Many Indians resented <PERSON> Rajneesh </PERSON> calling himself <PERSON> Bhagwan </PERSON> because, in <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION>, no mortal is equal to God. `` I have been calling myself ` <PERSON> Bhagwan </PERSON>' just as a challenge to this country,'' the 57-year-old who once taught philosophy in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> said in the statement from his new commune in <LOCATION> Poona </LOCATION>, western <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. `` I do n't want to be called ` <PERSON> Bhagwan </PERSON>.' Enough is enough. The joke is over,'' he said. <PERSON> Rajneesh </PERSON> was deported three years ago from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> after he pleaded guilty to immigration fraud and closed his 64,000-acre commune of <LOCATION> Rajneeshpuram </LOCATION> in central Oregon. Followers had bestowed dozens of Rolls Royces on their revered guide of Eastern religion, pop psychology and free love. After roaming in search of a new sanctuary for a claimed 500,000 faithful worldwide, he moved his cult to a six-acre commune in <LOCATION> Poona </LOCATION>, a city of nearly 1 million residents about 80 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Bombay </LOCATION>. But despite Thursday's announcement, the guru did not entirely renounce claims to divinity. He told 10,000 people in <LOCATION> Poona </LOCATION>, `` From today onwards, you can look at me as ` Gautama the Buddha.' And by accepting <PERSON> Gautama </PERSON> the <PERSON> Buddha </PERSON> as my very soul, I go out of the Hindu fold completely.'' <PERSON> Gautama </PERSON> <PERSON> Buddha </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> about 500 B.C., renounced a title too. Born a prince, he gave up nobility to launch a new religion _ Buddhism.
