<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While a nearly all-male club is making its annual New Year's Eve trek up 14,110-foot <PERSON> Pike </PERSON>'s Peak, a group of women will be making a 1,000-foot ascent of a nearby mountain in jest of the traditional event. This year's climb will mark the 66th annual climb of <PERSON> Pike </PERSON>'s Peak by the AdAmAn club, which plans to set off fireworks at the summit. The group adds a climber each year. AdaWoman, a band founded in 1982, will make an ascent on Pyramid Mountain in Ute Pass west of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, light sparklers, play <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Reddy </PERSON>'s song `` I Am Woman,'' down champagne and head home for the night, organizers said. It will be the seventh climb for the AdaWoman club, which was founded almost as a lark by <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> and several other woman who train on Pyramid Mountain. `` It's really beautiful up there, and one morning we had run the mountain and decided this was the way we should start out the new year together,'' she said. The women also were prodded that year because AdAmAn, for the first time in its history, was inviting a female guest, veteran climber <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>. `` One of the AdAmAn members said that the reason they had n't done it before was they did n't know any women who could make it,'' said <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON>. `` Well, I and another of our members ran the <ORGANIZATION> Pikes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marathon </ORGANIZATION>, so I think we can make it.'' AdAmAn historian <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> said <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, still the only woman invited, will make her fourth climb with the club this year. `` Of course, when we started this climb in 1922, you could n't have hired a woman to go with us It was n't until a few years ago that women got so they were into this type of thing,'' he said. <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> said AdaWoman may add a man in 50 or 60 years, if one is found worthy.
