<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> showed a little belated Christmas spirit when it agreed to tear up 800 parking tickets issued Monday to many car owners who thought it was a holiday. City Councilman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Giarrusso </PERSON> argued Thursday for giving auto owners the benefit of the doubt. City Attorney <PERSON> Okla </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> countered that the <ORGANIZATION> Streets </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had done nothing it was n't authorized to do. Several people cited for expired parking meters downtown and in the tourist-loaded French Quarter said they thought the day after Christmas was a ticket-free holiday. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said that Monday was a city government holiday not a public holiday, which would have been ticket free. Streets director <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> said she gets tired of defending the city holiday policy to irate drivers. `` We did n't gear up and lick our chops and think that we really had something to go for,'' <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> said. `` It was just a normal working day.''
