<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON>, will return to television for the first time in nearly two years Monday with a live show broadcast from their living room, a newspaper reported today. Six independent television stations across the nation will carry the program, said The Charlotte Observer, quoting unidentified sources. <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON>, who was indicted with three associates this month on charges of misusing millions of dollars in <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> money, could not be reached for comment Thursday. <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> has not had a regular TV show since resigning from <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> in March 1987 after widely publicized allegations of his 1980 sexual encounter with church secretary <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> and payments to keep her quiet. He and <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> were co-hosts of <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION>'s `` <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Show </PERSON>.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Bakkers </ORGANIZATION>' new show will be broadcast live from their living room near <LOCATION> Pineville </LOCATION> Monday through Friday and will be carried on stations in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Chico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, the Observer said. <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Toms </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hendersonville </LOCATION> said in a telephone interview Thursday night that the <ORGANIZATION> Bakkers </ORGANIZATION> had been preparing to return to television, but could not confirm when the return would take place. While at <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Bakkers </ORGANIZATIO