<HEAD>Bomb Explodes In Punjab Neighborhood, Kills 5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bomb exploded in a crowded neighborhood in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state today as police tried to defuse the device, killing at least five people and injuring 20, authorities said. The dead included a police inspector and two constables working to detach the bomb, which had been placed in a tin box and attached to a bicycle parked in a central <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> neighborhood, authorities said. No one claimed responsibility for the blast, which occurred at 7:30 a.m. But police said they suspected Sikh militants waging a 6-year guerrilla war against <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s Hindu majority for a separate homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, a prosperous farming state bordering <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. According to a police spokesman, an anonymous caller warned authorities of the bomb. Police Inspector <PERSON> Bhagat </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> and six assistants went to the neighborhood and as they tried to defuse the bomb, it exploded, killing <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> and constables <PERSON> Bachitar </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kishan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lal </PERSON>, the police spokesman said. Two men, a Sikh and a Hindu, also died. Twenty others, including several children on their way to school, were injured, the spokesman said. At least 10 were in serious condition, he said. Sikhs make up 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 880 million people, but they are a slight majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Hindus comprise more than 80 percent of the country's population. Sikh militants, claiming discrimination by the Hindu community, have been demanding an independent nation in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> since 1982. They have been blamed for more than 2,400 killings this year alone.
