<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     12-30 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Farmers Met Contracts Despite Drought, USDA Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The summer's devastating drought caused relatively few farmers to renege on contracts for advance sales of corn, soybeans and wheat, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says. The report by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said a survey of 325 elevators, or warehouses, in 13 Corn Belt and spring wheat states showed farmers would default on less than 1 percent of their contracts. `` Only about 1 percent of these elevators expected that losses from farmers failing to meet contract commitments would exceed 10 percent of the elevator's net worth,'' the report said. The report was ordered by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in this year's Disaster Assistance Act, which provided aid to farmers hit by the drought and hot weather during the spring and early summer months. Drought raised commodity prices sharply and left many farmers with less grain and soybeans to deliver than they had counted on when they entered into forward contracts early in the year. `` Many would have liked to get out of their contracts, if that were possible, because market prices rose above the contracted prices,'' the report said. `` Some farmers produced less than they had sold forward and faced buying out their contracts at a loss.'' If farmers defaulted, that would leave elevators or other buyers to absorb the losses. The report was sent to <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> but has not been distributed generally by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>. A copy was made available Thursday to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Most of the information was based on a telephone survey of the 325 elevators in September. The report said the survey results also were consistent with information obtained in field interviews of elevator managers, telephone interviews of bankers and brokers, and from state grain marketing specialists. `` Severe drought and the associated grain and soybean price increases hit farmers who priced forward in two ways,'' the report said. `` Those who hedged by selling futures were the first to be affected. To meet margin calls during the period when prices increased, these farmers had to either tap financial reserves or obtain increased credit.'' But the study found in a `` small-scale survey of commodity brokers and bankers'' that farmers and their brokers and bankers successfully weathered the sharp commodity price increases and the resulting calls for greater margins, or deposits, that occurred in June and July. `` For farmers who entered into cash forward contracts, the financial problem hit when it became necessary to buy back contracts in lieu of making delivery,'' the report said. More than half of the elevators surveyed had forward contracts with farmers for corn, soybeans or wheat produced in 1988. The contracts covered about 15 percent of the corn, 22 percent of the soybeans and 7 percent of the spring wheat that these elevators bought this year. According to the survey, the elevators indicated that more than 95 percent of their outstanding forward contracts with farmers likely would be fulfilled as originally negotiated, with between 1 percent and 2 percent renegotiated, and less than 1 percent in default. The remainder were uncertain. Officials had expected higher rates of default and renogotiation, but the report said many farmers realized the possible intensity of the drought by early June and curtailed normal contracting activity. `` As a result, farmers incurred fewer contract obligations than they might have incurred if the drought had not become apparent until later in the season,'' the report said. Weather also was important during that period, the report said. Many areas, particularly in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, received rain in late July and early August, which improved yield prospects in those areas. In those cases, improved yields helped farmers meet contract obligations, compared with the uncertainties of only a few weeks earlier. The 13 states included an eastern Corn Belt region of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, and a western Corn Belt region of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
