<HEAD>Experts Say Armenian Nuclear Plant Must be Reinforced or Shut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A nuclear plant in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> should be strengthened against earthquakes as quickly as possible or closed, experts were quoted as saying in an official report. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, the official Soviet news agency, said Thursday that specialists hurried to inspect the plant near <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, after the earthquake Dec. 7 that killed thousands of people. They concluded that the plant was not damaged but needed reinforcement against earthquakes `` within the shortest possible time'' or it should be closed, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The report follows an announcement by <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear power officials last week that six nuclear power projects were scrapped because of earthquake danger or because of tougher standards. New rules were imposed after the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear disaster in April 1986 killed at least 31 people. Speculation abounded after the earthquake earlier this month that the plant near <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> was damaged. The facility lies near a geological fault. Soviet Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> told reporters in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> on Dec. 12 that the plant would be shut in two years. But the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> story, quoting <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Velikhov </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, mentioned no deadline. The facility generates more than one-third of the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> mountain republic's electricity.
