<HEAD>Reagan Vows To Bring Jet Bombers To Justice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is pledging an all-out effort to bring those responsible for the `` savage and tragic'' bombing of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 to justice. `` What we want to do is find out who did it and bring them to justice,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in a statement Thursday before flying here from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to continue a two-week <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> vacation. When they arrived in <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, the president and <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> were greeted by the mayor of <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, entertainer <PERSON> Sonny </PERSON> <PERSON> Bono </PERSON>, and his wife. The <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> will be guests until Monday at the palatial desert home of publisher <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Annenberg </PERSON> in nearby <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mirage </LOCATION>, continuing their custom of attending a New Year's party there. The <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> then plan to return to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to spend a few more days in the Bel Air residence that will be their home after <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s term ends on Jan. 20. They are scheduled to fly back to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Jan. 5 for their final two weeks in the White House. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s statement at the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> airport was his first since British authorities announced more than 24 hours earlier that they had determined the crash was caused by a bomb. The crash killed 259 people in the air _ mostly Americans _ and 11 on the ground. `` I think you all know that I have been following quite closely the details of the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> 103 tragedy, and now that we know definitely that it was a bomb, we're going to make every effort we can to find out who is guilty of this savage and tragic thing and bring them to justice,'' the president said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, echoing comments made by officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> `` is studying and making recommendations as to additional things we can do at airports to provide security for those who travel.'' Asked whether he thought the bombing was the work of terrorists, the president said, `` I ca n't comment on that. It seems to savor of that, but we're going to have to have more details, and we're doing everything we can to find them and working in connection with other countries on that.'' British investigators announced in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Wednesday they have `` conclusive evidence'' that a bomb, not structural failure, caused the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> jumbo </ORGANIZATION> jet to break up Dec. 21 over southwestern <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>.
