<HEAD>Dollar Slips Against Yen In Last Trading Day Of Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar slipped today against the Japanese yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, ending the year's final trading day at 125.90 yen. After opening at 125.75 yen, down 0.28 yen from Thursday's closing, the dollar inched up but failed to regain its Thursday level It closed at 125.90 yen, down 0.13 yen, after ranging between 125.75 and 126.00 yen during the day. Dealers attributed the dollar's losses in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> to its decline on overseas markets Thursday. A dealer at a major commercial bank in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> described trading as `` very thin'' ahead of the three-day New Year's holiday starting Saturday. After beginning the year in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on Jan. 4 at 120.45 yen, its lowest level since modern exchange rates were established in the late 1940s, the dollar stayed mostly between 120 and 130 yen in the first half of the year. However, in the second half it fluctuated between the low-120 yen and mid-130 yen levels. After peaking at 136.75 yen on Sept. 2, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency began declining to a low closing of 120.88 yen on Nov. 25. Since then it has remained generally within the 120-126 yen range. Currency dealers said more stability is expected in exchange rates in 1989 unless President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> makes drastic changes in his economic policy from that of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. `` But unless the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> succeeds in trimming its twin deficits, the general tendency will be toward a weaker dollar against a stronger yen,'' said a dealer at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial bank in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> will reopen Jan. 4.
