<HEAD>Former Philippine President Returns to Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> president <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was hospitalized in guarded condition with possible congestive heart failure or pneumonia, hospital officials said. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, who contends he is too ill to travel to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for arraignment on racketeering charges, entered <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday for the second time in three weeks. `` They -LRB- the attending physicians -RRB- have diagnosed him as a possible congestive heart failure or pneumonia,'' said <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> nursing supervisor <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, 71, was listed in guarded condition. A leading <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> supporter, said a priest administered the last rites to <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, but a <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> spokesman could not provide confirmation. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> is `` very, very seriously ill,'' said the supporter, Friends of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> President <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Lazo </PERSON>. `` We are preparing a telegram to send to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, asking them to let him -LRB- <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> -RRB- go home. That is his dying wish.'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Gemmo </PERSON> <PERSON> Trinidad </PERSON> said he did not know if a priest had administered the sacrament of the sick, formerly known as extreme unction. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was brought to the hospital by ambulance at 4:55 p.m., said <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Kop </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION> said he was with <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> when he was taken to the hospital, but