<HEAD>Mayor Barry Says He May Take Drug Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> admitted visiting an acquaintance suspected of drug involvement `` caused some embarrassment'' for the city but said he was innocent of wrongdoing and would be `` extra, extra careful'' to avoid appearances of impropriety in his personal life. The city's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney, meanwhile, said Thursday that his office had decided to conduct a full investigation of the incident, in which the mayor visited a former city employee at a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> hotel just as police were preparing to attempt an undercover drug buy from the man. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, in today's editions, quoted an unidentified source as saying the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> may join the federal investigation. Police have turned over to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> results of an internal probe into why two detectives were stopped from attempting a drug buy from former city employee <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> after <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> turned up at <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>' hotel room. The incidence occurred a week ago. Earlier this week, federal prosecutors had said only that they were reviewing what police investigators had found. But on Thursday, <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said his office `` is conducting a full investigation of this entire matter.'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, through spokesmen, has repeatedly denied any wrongdoing. On Thursday he called a news conference to answer questions `` around the controversy'' and he vigorously denied using or seeing drugs in the hotel room. `` I believe that one is innocent until proven guilty,'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said. `` But since last Thursday, I have been tried, convicted, sentenced and doing time, by some members of the media.'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> has acknowledged making several visits to <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, whom he described as an acquaintance, but denied any involvement with drugs. Asked in a separate interview on <ORGANIZATION> WJLA-TV </ORGANIZATION> whether he would submit to a drug test, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> responded, `` I would do anything necessary to get this issue behind us.'' He said he would discuss it with his doctor `` and he'll tell me what to do.'' Asked if that meant he would take the drug test if his doctor approved, the mayor said he would, `` absolutely.'' However, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>'s spokesman, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, said earlier that no purpose would be served by such a test since `` he does n't do drugs.'' The police investigation, according to sources, was focused on whether <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> was involved in any drug activity, why the mayor was in the hotel, and why the police officers did not search <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>' hotel room until after he had checked out Friday morning Hotel employees, police sources said, initially had complained that <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> had offered drugs in return for sex. `` The public needs to know what happened,'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said. `` I still have demanded and call for a complete investigation and a complete disclosure of this report so this city can get on with its business.'' At the beginning of the news conference, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> promised to provide details on his relationship with <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, but he revealed only that he met <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> when <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> worked for the district government. The mayor refused to answer reporters' questions after finishing his remarks. While city employees applauded <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> as he marched from the council chambers, others were not impressed with the mayor's comments `` He had an opportunity to talk to the nation, and he missed that opportunity,'' said <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON>. `` There were a lot of unanswered questions.'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>'s latest controversy refocuses scrutiny on his personal life. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, who is married, acknowledged last year he once had a `` personal'' relationship with a convicted cocaine dealer, <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. However, he denied buying cocaine from her or using drugs with her, and denied reports she had been paid hush money. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> had been jailed on contempt charges three years earlier after refusing to testify before a grand jury. Officials say the case remains under investigation.
