<HEAD>Former Health Official And Early Critic Of Rocky Flats Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHEAT RIDGE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dr. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, an early and outspoken critic of the <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flats </ORGANIZATION> nuclear weapons plant, has died of complications from heart surgery. He was 59. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> died Thursday at the <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in this <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> suburb, his son, <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON>, said. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> was forced to resign as <LOCATION> Jefferson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> health director in May 1981, following his publication of studies showing a higher incidence of cancer in areas of <LOCATION> Jefferson </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> counties close to the Rocky Flats plant 16 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> sued numerous county officials over the firing. He received a $ 150,000 settlement in January 1985. `` They fired the messenger for the message,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Holland </PERSON>, the attorney who represented <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> in the case. `` They killed off the community's public health director for proving that the community had a major illness. `` To me, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> was truly a great man ... His death is a tragedy in that it's too early.'' <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> said <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> `` accomplished a great portion of his mission which was to revitalize the people's right to live in a safe setting.'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s supporters said the government is now starting to acknowledge points he had been making for years. For example, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> recently compiled a modernization report which calls for improvements to the nation's nuclear weapons facilities through the year 2010 According to a summary of the $ 250 billion <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> plan, <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flats </ORGANIZATION>' recycling buildings would be upgraded between 1990 and 1997 to continue operating safely as the plant is gradually shut down and relocated. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> recently had been doing consulting work on the effects of nuclear radiation, <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> said. He wrote and published articles, including a Dec. 18 column in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, headlined `` Rocky Flats: <ORGANIZATION> Death </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'' `` If the nation is to be properly protected, all studies of nuclear contamination and associated health effects should be conducted primarily by independent scientists who are insulated from cynical retaliation,'' he wrote. The Sims, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, native received his medical degree in 1965 from <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>. He also held a master's degree in public health from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> He became <LOCATION> Jefferson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> health director in 1973. Following his resignation, he spent five years as a medical officer with the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dakota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGA