<HEAD>Transcript of Pentagon Briefing on Base Closings Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a condensed transcript of the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> briefing Thursday on recommendations by the <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> secretary's commission on military base closings Participants were Deputy Defense Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> IV and commission co-chairmen <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Ribicoff </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. RIBICOFF: We believe the results reflect a balanced report to eliminate unnecessary installation capacity without restricting the flexibility of our national security managers during future mobilizations, contingencies and changes in the international political environment. The recommended changes reflect an opportunity to improve the nation's defense position. EDWARDS: We would like to take this opportunity ... to thank the department and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for this opportunity to participate in a unique effort, which will not only save taxpayers dollars, but also improve our national defense posture. During the course of developing our recommendations, we used improvement in military value of our domestic base structure as the preeminent consideration. Our report presents an opportunity to reduce training costs in terms of manpower, overhead costs and fuel, to improve command and control, to consolidate training and improve economies of scale, and to remove unnecessary administrative burdens to our defense managers. Add to these improvements an opportunity to eliminate some future military construction costs and to save almost $ 700 million a year in base operating costs with a 20-year net present value of $ 5.6 billion. Despite these improvements, we do not anticipate any substantial socio-economic disruption to the communities that are closely linked with bases recommended for closure. In terms of environmental impact, we see little negative impact from these recommendations, and in many instances, improvement for the natural surroundings. RIBICOFF: There are 145 installations affected. There are 86 for closure, five for partial closure, 54 bases have been realigned. The estimation is $ 693 million saved per year in base operating costs and $ 5.6 billion to be saved over 20 years on the net present value. ... There are about 20 major ones. EDWARDS: I guess generally you would look at the <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION> area _ <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> George </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> base in <LOCATION> Norton </LOCATION>. Generally, you would look in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Chanute </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sheridan </LOCATION>. Generally, you would probably look at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Devens </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> national capital region area which would include <PERSON> Meade </PERSON>, <PERSON> Belvoir </PERSON> and Holabird. You would look at perhaps <ORGANIZATION> Pease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> up in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. I guess those are the big areas. RIBICOFF: It goes from page 52 to page 69 -LRB- in the report -RRB-, and I think you will find that to be a very accurate explanation of the rationale and what is happening to those bases. EDWARDS: -LRB- Fort -RRB- Dix -LRB- <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> -RRB- is going into what we call `` semi-active status.'' There will be a group of probably 500 or so people there who will maintain it, have it available for Reserve activity, have it available for active duty training from time to time, have it available in the event troops are brought home from some part of the world. It will be there to support <ORGANIZATION> McGuire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- and -RRB- the naval station at <LOCATION> Lakehurst </LOCATION>. We broke down all of the military facilities into various categories. And in our breakdown, <PERSON> Dix </PERSON> came out at the bottom of the list in a category where we had excess capacity _ basic training, advanced individual training and these types of things. We have moved those kinds of activities from <PERSON> Dix </PERSON> to various facilities in the country, some to <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Knox </LOCATION>, some to <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Leonard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, some to <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION> And in the process, we moved some out of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bliss </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, so all of it becomes compatible. What we've tried to do is bring training areas together to the extent that we could, where we could justify it. Q. You mentioned in your opening statement that you did n't expect any of these -LRB- communities -RRB- to be adversely affected by this. I think a lot of the communities will find that hard to swallow. EDWARDS: Of course they will. I said `` substantial socio-economic impact.'' Of course they will have a hard time swallowing it. ... There are some areas where the impact is obviously larger than others. But we have a section in here ... that deals with ways in which communities can help themselves when they feel this kind of impact. The Office of Economic Adjustment in the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has a great ability to move in and help a community work out its problems. Where possible, we have not moved troops across the country but next door, in the same state or in an adjoining state. Q. Perhaps you could tell me what sort of thinking went into your decision to close the Presidio in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>? EDWARDS: The Presidio sits in the middle of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> or thereabouts, and it ca n't grow. It ca n't do any more than it's doing There's no way it can expand. It's prohibited by laws of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and other laws as far as expansion is concerned. It's in a high-value area, and the operations at the Presidio can be done by and large most anywhere.
</TEXT>
