<FIRST>r w PM-BaseClosingsTranscript 1stAdd   12-30 0866</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Base Closings Transcript, 1st Add,0882</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: most anywhere.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Q. To what extent does the property value of these bases that you've chosen play a role in your decision ... and how many total jobs are we talking about here being lost? EDWARDS: The first thing we looked at was military value, without a doubt. I mean, that was our touchstone. And if a base had military value, then we did n't bother it. If the base was lacking in military value, then it became a candidate to look at. We obviously did not ignore cost savings. We used ... as our guideline a six-year payback, as set out in the charter. And so if a facility did not meet the six-year payback, then it's not in our list. In some instances, we looked at estimates as to what we could sell the property for, but it was not the cornerstone of our activity. Q. How about the jobs question? EDWARDS: I do n't know whether we actually totaled all that. You'll see a column that talks about personnel out and personnel in, both military and civilian. And I think if you'll ust run your finger down the column to the area you're looking for, you'll see the impact. Q. Is this the end of it, in your mind? Or can a year from now a similar commission come back and recommend a similar number of bases? I mean, a $ 5.6 billion savings over a certain number of years is rather insignificant when you consider the total defense budget. RIBICOFF: We think the basic responsibility should be in the hands of the secretary of defense. There should be an ongoing study to see what changes should be made in the bases. We've recommended that there should be a high-level, small group of people to go over this with the secretary of defense, but I would hope that there would n't always be a commission like ours that would be necessary to do the whole job over again. The training is altogether different with the new technology. We're going to have to acquire larger tracts of land. Many of the present bases are limited because they have been surrounded by large urban areas and their effectiveness has been destroyed. So I think the country is going to have to take a good, hard look, and the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, as to what future training will have to be for future wars and the changes that are going to take place. Q. Can you tell us what the up-front costs of closing and realigning these bases are? EDWARDS: Well, let's see, the <ORGANIZATION> Najavo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Depot </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, just to pull one out of there. It's going to cost $ 11 million to make that move. But it will pay back in annual savings $ 3.05 million. And so it's going to take us four years to recover that initial cost of the move before we start making annual savings. But then they are annual savings forever. Q. As two former members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, how do you think ... the reaction on the Hill will be to this? EDWARDS: I believe the leadership of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committees </ORGANIZATION>, of both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, favor this exercise taking place. There's no question that many congressmen and senators are going to be upset when they see this list, especially if it affects -LRB- their -RRB- community. I would anticipate, from my own general conversations ... from the time we were appointed to the present, that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will accept it. Q. There are some lawmakers, especially from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, who have already argued that the ... the state has been unfairly hit here. Your reaction to that? EDWARDS: A lot of the activity in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> that is reported in here has to do with <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON>. They are both encroached by air traffic congestion from the <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION> airport. They ca n't train adequately because of that problem. They both have major problems in attracting high-technology employees because of the activity in that area in the civilian sector. And we felt that we really just had no alternative but to deal with that. Mather -LRB- Air Force Base, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> -RRB-, they are a good distance away from their training area. They have to fly over 150 nautical miles just to get to the area where they train their particular aircraft and pilots. We have moved them into <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Home </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, where there is an electronic training range right there. ... I like to think there's a rationale to what we've done. RIBICOFF: I think they -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- recognize the great changes that have taken place in training with the present type of equipment and the present time of aircraft and what has happened in the urban areas, and they realize that changes have to be made. And <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> ... is the fastest growing state in the Union, when it comes to urban encroachment and the elimination of open spaces that air forces need. Q. What happens if the list is rejected by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>? Will you gentlemen start over? EDWARDS: We are a one-shot, unique kind of an organization. When we hand this report over, we are finished.
</TEXT>
