 RIBICOFF: It just goes to prove that there's still a lot of work to be done, and it should be ongoing. And I would hope the next secretary of defense would take this job very, very seriously. ... There's money to be saved. And with tight budget restraints, you're going to have to save it wherever you can for basic important purposes in the defense establishment Q. Some of the bases are under construction, such as the naval station in <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. What's the rationale for closing that? The state of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> has already spent $ 8 million building a highway to it. EDWARDS: My recollection is that we could save $ 8 million a year forever. -LRB- Laughter. -RRB- We concluded that <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> was primarily a reserve center in the home port plan, that <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> had only had one oiler and one minesweeper, and that they could be moved to <LOCATION> Engleside </LOCATION>, so that we would put together in one place in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> the carrier, the battleship and the support ships. That's the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. Then on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, you would have the Pascagoula-Mobile-Pensacola complex. So you'd have two complexes on the Gulf instead of whatever they were. Q. Some of the bases have been on hit lists. Things have changed over the years. The base that led to the obstructing legislation was <ORGANIZATION> Loring </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. What has changed over the years to make that cold-weather base, which was considered obsolete in 1977, necessary now? REP. EDWARDS: I ca n't give you chapter and verse, because it did n't come through on our six-year payback. ... One of the things we had to deal with was the fact that a lot of the bases that were along the coast, such as <PERSON> Pease </PERSON>, the airplanes that would go in a base like that are better centrally located in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because of the time it takes for the Soviets or some enemy to get a missile lobbed in. And you do n't need them right up on the front lines anymore. Q. Did you at all assess the impact on defense contractors that support these facilities? EDWARDS: We did not. RIBICOFF: No. Q. I could not find <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monroe </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> -RRB- anywhere. Who saved it? EDWARDS: Me. -LRB- Laughter. -RRB- I personally went to <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monroe </LOCATION> to look at it. And I saw the moat and ... the old historic buildings. ... I also saw what would amount to around $ 900 million in cleanup costs to get rid of the old shells that had been lobbed over on part of that fort for the last 200 years or however long it was. I also saw the cost of building new facilities to house all of those people _ 3,000 or 4,000 people as I recall _ and it just did n't even come close to our six-year payback. It was more like a 20-year payback at best. And in part because there's no real market value for that property. It would become, perhaps, a museum one day. ... I do n't know any developer in his right mind who would want to go in there and buy that property
