<SECOND>PM-Big Ape,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans, Vietnamese To Excavate Remains Of Giant Ape</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American scientists today said they will join Vietnamese archeologists in a remote cave outside <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> to search for remains of the largest known ape _ a 9-foot primate that became extinct 200,000 years ago. The excavation, planned for Jan. 4-28, is being billed as the first field research project involving scientists of the two countries since the beginning of the war in <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION>. Paleoanthropologist <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciochon </PERSON> said he and three other Americans would join about 10 Vietnamese scientists at the limestone cave where remains have been found of the `` Gigantopithecus,'' an ape known only from sites in southern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. Despite some earlier research by Vietnamese, East German and French scientists, very little is known about the giant, which is related to the orangutan, chimpanzee and gorilla. Only jawbones and teeth of the animal have been uncovered but <PERSON> Ciochon </PERSON> said the team hoped to find more remains in the cave, 75 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>, which served as a weapons depot and bomb shelter during the Vietnam War. `` One thing we know about it is that it was very big,'' <PERSON> Ciochon </PERSON> told reporters. It was probably a four-footed, vegetarian animal weighing about 770 pounds that became extinct 200,000 to 300,000 years ago, the Americans said. There is speculation early man may have hunted the ape to extinction. The team hopes to establish relationships between `` homo erectus,'' the direct ancestor of modern humans, stone tools used by early man and the giant ape since the remains of all three have been found in the area of the cave. <PERSON> Ciochon </PERSON>, from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION>, said the Americans were bringing in special rock saws and generators for the excavation. He said these would be turned over to Vietnamese counterparts when the Americans returned home. Two Vietnamese scientists are to visit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> later, bringing fossils from the excavation site. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, which is sending a team to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to film a documentary on the excavation, is the main backer of the expedition. Although the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> have no diplomatic relations, informal exchanges have increased the past two years. However, <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> permits far more American academics, journalists and others to visit <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> than <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> does Vietnamese to enter the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ciochon </PERSON> said members of his team had visited <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> in 1987 and 1988 for preliminary surveys. <PERSON> Ciochon </PERSON> said research on the Gigantopithecus in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has been hampered by site disturbances: remains of the ape have been ground up to be sold as medicine. In <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, he said, this practice does not exist and the potential of finding substantial fossil remains is considerable. Other American members of the expedition are Ms. <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Semendeferi </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Olsen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilliland </PERSON> <PERSON> Olsen </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION>. The Vietnamese scientists come from the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archaeology </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
