<HEAD>Racial Strife Spreads To Hangzhou Over AIDS Rumor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Racial strife involving African students has spread to a second Chinese city, with Africans at a university in <LOCATION> Hangzhou </LOCATION> protesting rumors they were carriers of the disease AIDS. About 65 Africans attending <ORGANIZATION> Zhejiang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hangzhou </LOCATION> have stayed in their dormitory since Monday, boycotting classes and demanding to leave <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, a student from <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION> said. He said university officials have blocked attempts to leave the eastern <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> city. The student, speaking on condition of anonymity, said university officials had implied they were carriers of the fatal disease AIDS. `` They treat us like criminals,'' he said. Further details of the dispute were inpeded by poor telephone connections. University officials were not available for comment. <LOCATION> Hangzhou </LOCATION> is about 140 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>, scene of five days of anti-African demonstrations stemming from a Christmas Eve fight between African students and Chinese. Chinese officials have isolated about 140 African students and other foreign sympathizers in a remote guest house outside the city to protect them from <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> demonstrators demanding Africans responsible for injuring 11 Chinese be brought to justice. The Chinese side has refused the Africans' request to leave <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>, and only those students who agree to return to their schools are being allowed to leave the guest house. Almost all the Africans say they fear for their safety and will not return to the city. The <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>'s leading daily, ran a front-page story today for the second straight day expressing understanding for the anger of the Chinese youth a