<HEAD>Pepperidge Farm To Remove Tropical Oils From Crackers, Cookies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man who spent $ 2 million to pressure the food industry into making healthier products says he's pleasantly surprised by <ORGANIZATION> Pepperidge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to stop using coconut oil in crackers and cookies. `` Ultimately Pepperidge Farms will have saved thousands of lives,'' <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Sokolof </PERSON> said Thursday. Coconut oil is a saturated fat that raises cholesterol levels. People who have high levels of cholesterol run a higher risk of clogged arteries that can lead to heart disease. <ORGANIZATION> Pepperidge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> announced Wednesday that it would stop using coconut oil in numerous products, including its popular `` Original Goldfish,'' in response to `` strong consumer concern.'' `` Frankly, I'm surprised, because <ORGANIZATION> Pepperidge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> has a multimillion-dollar undertaking on their hands to change their products,'' said <PERSON> Sokolof </PERSON>, founder of the Nebraska-based National Heart Savers. Pepperidge Farm will have to come up with new recipes for more than 50 brands of cookies and crackers, said <PERSON> Sokolof </PERSON>, whose group has campaigned against products using tropical oils. `` We must find oils that will proximate tropical oils in terms of performance in the baking process, flavor, texture, mouth-feel and shelf-life stability,'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shea </PERSON>, president of the Norwalk-based company, said in a statement issued Wednesday. Coconut and palm oil are popular with food manufacturers because they help extend the shelf life of food products, <PERSON> Sokolof </PERSON> said. Many products advertised as being free of cholesterol contain tropical oils that can help cholesterol form after consumption, he said. Coconut oil contains 100 percent more saturated fat than lard. <PERSON> Sokolof </PERSON> placed advertisments in newspapers in October depicting nine products he says are portrayed as healthy foods, but are `` poisoning'' Americans with saturated fats. A 65-year-old multimillionaire who nearly died from a heart attack in 1966, <PERSON> Sokolof </PERSON> has spent $ 2 million to pressure food industry giants into making healthier products. His father and a brother-in-law died of heart attacks.
