<HEAD>North Korea Mass Producing Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is producing chemical weapons at eight plants and organizing chemical warfare units to help maintain superiority over South Korean and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces, officials said today. A report by the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> disclosed for the first time that <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> was producing chemical weapons, including poison gas, at eight cities, including Sinhung and <LOCATION> Sinuju </LOCATION>. Chemical weapons would probably be used to knock out <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces as part of lightning attacks if the North invaded, officials said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has 42,000 troops based in the South under a defense pact. The report, part of an overview on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and North Korean military forces, said the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> also has six storage sites for chemical weapons and three research and development centers. Storage centers are located near the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> border for possible use in a war, the report said. Chemical weapons factories are based in the north of the country, with many close to the Chinese and Soviet borders, it said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they were aware of reports of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s chemical warfare capability, but declined to comment further. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> had formed chemical warfare units and attached them to infantry regiments, officials said. The North is expected to eventually deploy chemical, they said. The North is also producing Soviet-designed `` Scud'' and `` Frog'' missiles with ranges of up to 180 miles that could be used to deliver chemical warheads, officials said. The officials could not say when chemical weapons might be deployed by <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. They noted that the North had been developing chemical weapons since the 1960s. South Korean and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces have anti-chemical warfare gear, such as gas masks and chemical warfare suits. The two governments decline to say if they deploy chemical weapons in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> reportedly possess battlefield nuclear weapons, but <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> refuses to confirm or deny the reports. The South Korean report noted that <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> is making advances in building up its defenses and expects to end the North's military superiority by the start of the next century. But it said that <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> still has a substantial edge in troops and weapons and was producing large numbers of tanks, artillery pieces, rockets and other weapons. North and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> have been conducting talks aimed at easing tensions, but the bitter rivals have hundreds of thousands of heavily-armed troops poised along their border. The two nations were formed after <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet forces ended the Japanese occupation at the end of the Second World War in 1945. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> invaded the South in 1950, prompting the bloody three-year Korean War.
