dition of anonymity, refused to comment in detail about the explosives experts among the 2,500 civilians and 200 military at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Halstead </LOCATION> and three other sites operated by the establishment. Explosives work centers around <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Halstead </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Sevenoaks </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Kent </LOCATION> about 20 miles southeast of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. `` It's a high-security installation, which is very expert in matters of explosives and armaments research,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON>, a professor and terrorism expert at <ORGANIZATION> Aberdeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. `` Their reputation is extremely high,'' he said in an interview, adding that Fort Halstead experts would have worked closely with experts in the Scottish town of <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, which bore the brunt of the crash, to get a `` broader picture'' of the crash. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Learmount </PERSON>, air transport editor of the respected aviation journal <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, said that when investigators announced they were taking a suitcase and pieces of wreckage to <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Halstead </LOCATION> for tests, he knew they were looking for `` symptoms of an explosion.'' Investigators said the tests found residues of explosives in two parts of a `` luggage pallet'' _ the metal rack in the baggage hold in which luggage is stored. But they said they still did n't know where the bomb was planted and how it was brought aboard. <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Geldard </PERSON>, head of research at the privately funded <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> For </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Study </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZ