 A bomb exploded today near a newsstand in a <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> suburb, and police said they suspected ultra-Orthodox militants were trying to block the sale of papers they consider pornographic. The bomb exploded in Ramat Gan, causing no injuries but minor damage to a store, and police demolition experts dismantled four bombs in nearby <LOCATION> Bnei </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brak </LOCATION>, police spokesman <PERSON> Dalia </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilad </PERSON> said. She said different types of bombs were used, but that at least one was a firebomb. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio described it as a firebomb equipped with a timer. <PERSON> Gilad </PERSON> said no group claimed responsibility, but police suspect it was the work of ultra-Orthodox militants. `` The bombs were all found in places where secular newspapers are sold,'' <PERSON> Gilad </PERSON> said. Ultra-Orthodox Jews object to pictures that show unmarried men and women together, or women in revealing clothing. The deputy mayor of <LOCATION> Bnai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brak </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shmuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON>, said the attempted bombings were the work of `` disturbed people'' and were not sanctioned by the religious community. `` According to our past experience, when the police did catch somebody, they were disturbed people who saw the bombings as some kind of a religious commandment,'' he said. Last August, five bombs were placed near newsstands in <LOCATION> Bnei </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brak </LOCATION>. Three of the bombs exploded, causing minor damage but no injuries, and two were dismantled by police. The ultra-Orthodox Agudat <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> party condemned the latest bombing attempts, saying they violated Jewish scriptures. `` Violence is not the way of the Torah,'' the party said in a statement. `` We are convinced that it was done by radicals rejected by the Orthodox public.''
