<HEAD>Grandfather Kills Handicapped Grandson, Then Himself</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> says her father was apparently trying to relieve her of the hardship of caring for a handicapped child when he killed his 2-year-old grandson, then took his own life. `` He was the kind of person who did n't want to be burdened in his own life and did n't want me to be burdened by my child,'' Ms. Day said Thursday. The <LOCATION> Lewis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's department found the bodies of 75-year-old Hollis Day and little <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> on Wednesday night in Day's locked <PERSON> Jeep </PERSON> <PERSON> Waggoner </PERSON> Grandfather and grandson had been missing since Tuesday morning. The bodies were found on wooded, family-owned land 50 miles from the Day home. The gun lay near the bodies. Both had been shot in the head. Ms. <PERSON> Day </PERSON> said she began worrying a few hours after finding a note that read, `` Gramps and <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> have gone bye-bye together.'' `` He was having dreams, you know, of he and my son floating off into the air and reliving all these things in the hereafter _ the ... hunting and skiing and fishing trips,'' the 40-year-old woman recalled. Her father had greeted her with an extra warm hug when she woke up Tuesday morning, and told her that she was a wonderful girl and mother, Ms. <PERSON> Day </PERSON> said. She asked him to take care of <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> while she packed up Christmas gifts to head home for <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, and then learned the two had taken off together in Day's vehicle, <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> hastily wrapped in a coat and hat over his pajamas. Ms. Day, <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> and the boy's father, <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Berreth </PERSON>, had been visiting her parents. She found the note and, a few hours later, the tenor of its words suddenly merged with what her father had been saying in recent months, and it hit her: `` Bye-bye'' meant eternity. She called police, indicating a suicide was possible. `` At this point, the evidence appears consistent with a homicide-suicide theory,'' <LOCATION> Lewis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Logan </PERSON> said. Day, the retired president of a clothing company, had been scheduled for cataract surgery Thursday, and he was `` very very disturbed about my child's condition,'' she said. <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON>, her only child, suffered from a mild form of cerebral palsy, and was considered developmentally disabled, Ms. <PERSON> Day </PERSON> said. `` When you have a handicapped child, they're a little bit more work and he thought that having a child like that would be a total altering of my lifestlye that he did n't want to see imposed upon a daughter that he loved dearly. But it was n't in my wildest dreams that he'd do this.'' But her son was `` doing just fine,'' in a hospital therapy program, she said. `` He was beginning to walk and talk ... He was a gregarious, outgoing, happy, loving, affectionate child. He was a beautiful child. ... He would have been walking eventually. ... He was not retarded _ he was a slow learner.'' With more sadness than anger, she said her father was probably just trying to help, but had been losing his ability to think rationally.
