<HEAD>Boston Museum To Return Purloined Tomb Artifacts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> is returning to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> some fragments of nine ancient paintings because curators have concluded the art was stolen from a 15th century B.C. tomb. The museum bought the paintings from an art dealer in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, in 1978 for an undisclosed sum and they are not considered archaeologically significant, museum officials said Thursday. The artifacts probably will be returned in the spring after a representative of the <ORGANIZATION> Egyptian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Antiquities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> comes to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> to supervise packing and shipping, said Museum Director <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Shestack </PERSON>. <PERSON> Shestack </PERSON> ordered research into the paintings last year, after the museum's Egyptian art department expressed suspicions about the legality of their origin. The museum decided to return the artifacts voluntarily because they apparently were stolen, smuggled out of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and sold into the art world, museum officials said. The fragments came from the Theban tomb of Minnakht, an official in the period of Thutmose III, and date to 1450-1420 B.C., said <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kendall </PERSON>, the museum's acting curator of Egyptian and ancient Near Eastern art. The tomb is located in the Nobles Tombs at <LOCATION> Luxor </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. Thutmose was considered the greatest pharaoh of the 18th dynasty, known for conquests that extended <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> to the banks of the <LOCATION> Euphrates </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and the fourth cataract of the <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in what is now the <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. The fragments depict men and women bearing offerings, but most of the figures are only partly preserved, <PERSON> Kendall </PERSON> said. The largest fragment is about 1 foot long and 10 inches high. The <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> dealer who sold the objects to the museum has since died, <PERSON> Shestack </PERSON> said.
