<HEAD>Safety Council: 350-450 May Die in New Year's Weekend Traffic
Accidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Between 350 and 450 people could die in traffic accidents on the nation's highways during the three-day New Year's holiday weekend, according to estimates by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> The Chicago-based council said millions of Americans would drive an estimated 11.5 billion miles during the three-day observance, which for counting purposes extends from 6 p.m. local time Friday to midnight Monday. In addition to the deaths, between 16,000 and 21,000 people may suffer serious injuries as a result of traffic accidents during the New Year's holiday period, the council said. About 330 people could be expected to die during a normal three-day period at this time of the year, the council said. Last year, 375 people were killed during a four-day New Year's observance The worst New Year's toll recorded was 1965, when 564 people were killed during a three-day period. During the recent Christmas holiday weekend, at least 387 people were killed in traffic accidents, the council said.
