<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gunfire killed two people and wounded 28 during demonstrations over steep price increases and demands for an end to <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s civil war, a senior official said today. Demonstrators took to the streets for a fourth consecutive day today, even though the government canceled the price increases because of the protests, and a general strike continued to paralyze much of the country. <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Fatih </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdoun </PERSON> reported the shooting incident, saying `` an unidentified gunman'' caused the casualties when he opened fire on protesters near Cabinet offices Thursday. <PERSON> Abdoun </PERSON> gave no details. Other reports conflicted with his account but did not mention casualties. `` The action in the streets is taking on a definite anti-government flavor,'' said a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat who closely follows Sudanese affairs from <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s capital. `` It looks like the government is in serious trouble,'' he told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview. `` There is a lot of talk about a coup attempt coming out of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> ... There is complete political chaos.'' A crisis caused by an air traffic controllers' strike appeared to have ended today. An air traffic controller in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, closed since Wednesday night as part of the general strike, was reopened around 11 a.m. Two news dispatches received in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> on Thursday reported shooting near the Cabinet offices. The timing of the reports indicated there were two separate shootings. Neither mentioned casualties. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, in an early afternoon dispatch, quoted the official <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> as saying Sudanese police opened fire on demonstrators when they refused to disperse after being told that an emergency Cabinet session had rolled back the price increases. Reports said demonstrators also were chanting slogans calling for government action to implement a tentative peace plan. In <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, the official <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said in a Khartoum-datelined report Thursday night that shooting occurred shortly after dark in the Sudanese capital, `` especially near the headquarters of the Council of Ministers.'' Commissioner <PERSON> Abdoun </PERSON>'s version of the shooting conflicted with the Sudanese agency's report on the source of gunfire, and it was impossible to tell whether he and the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> news agency referred to the same incident. Another version came from the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, which based its reports on the Sudanese Ministry of Information. It said one person was reported injured Thursday in `` generally peaceful'' large-scale demonstrations in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, some at the university. Sudanese police used tear gas and `` warning shots'' to disperse the protesters, it said. Strikes and demonstrations were prompted by a government decree on Monday increasing sugar prices by 500 percent and cigarettes by 50 percent, and imposing a 15 percent sales tax on all commodities. Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>'s Cabinet met in emergency session Thursday morning and revoked the price increases. The Cabinet also considered the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unionist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s withdrawal from the governing coalition Wednesday night The Unionists held the second-largest number of ministerial and parliamentary seats after <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Umma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The party quit the government to protest the price increases and <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>'s failure to act on a tentative peace accord that a <ORGANIZATION> Unionist </ORGANIZATION> leader negotiated last month with rebel leader <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Garang </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> did not submit the accord to the Cabinet or the <ORGANIZATION> Constituent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s parliament, for endorsement because he feared that would prompt the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> to leave his coalition. The front, led by <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>'s brother-in-law, Attorney General <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Turabi </PERSON>, opposed the peace accord's stipulation that <ORGANIZATION> Sharia </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s legal and ethical code, be suspended during peace talks and that alternatives be considered The mainly Christian and animist southern rebels demand revocation of <LOCATION> Sharia </LOCATION>, imposed in 1983 by President <PERSON> Gaafar </PERSON> <PERSON> Nimeiri </PERSON> 18 months before he was overthrown in a 1985 military coup.
