<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> and Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganhdi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> held their second private meeting today as they sought to end four decades of friction between their countries. Sources said the meetings, which have overshadowed a summit involving seven south <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> nations, have been amicable and productive. `` They're getting along famously,'' an Indian source said. `` Their meetings are going well,'' said another Indian official. Both demanded anonymity. The leaders met following a regular summit session with the leaders of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bhutan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Maldives </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. The fourth annual summit of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> comes only four weeks after Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> took office following <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s first free election in 11 years. The summit has kindled hopes of closer ties between <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, historically antagonistic nations. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> spoke warmly of Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> in his speech at the opening session Thursday night. `` I am particularly happy to be here when the people of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> have elected you, Madam Prime Minister, to lead your great country forward to peace and prosperity, rooted in democracy. ... We rejoice in the prospect of friendship and cooperation between <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said. After the 2 -LCB- - hour opening session, <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Sonia </PERSON>, met privately over dinner with Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> and her husband, businessman <PERSON> Asif </PERSON> <PERSON> Zardari </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s session this afternoon was to last up to two hours _ much longer than those she scheduled with other visiting leaders. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> are to meet again Saturday after the summit ends. Although Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> did not refer to <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> in her inaugural speech, she said last week that continued animosity between <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> did not serve the interest of their peoples. The two countries have fought three wars since they were partitioned in 1947 upon the demise of British colonial <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Relations have further been strained by a border dispute over <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION>, which was split between <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> when the subcontinent was divided. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> claims part of the territory in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Protesters have demonstrated daily in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> against <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s claim <PERSON> Sardar </PERSON> <PERSON> Qayyum </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>, president of the Pakistan-controlled part of <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION>, said the protests `` have mobilized Kashmiris on this side of the cease-fire line and have shown our integrity and solidarity with those suffering on the other side.'' Other areas of friction between the nations include fears of each other's nuclear capabilities and claims that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has supported Sikh separatists who have killed 2,400 people this year in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s border state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has denied the charges. So far, Pakistani and Indian officials have declined to comment on the prospects of Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> visiting <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> soon. She has said her first foreign trips will be to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. She is expected to make a pilgrimage to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, site of Islam's holiest shrine, in January, but no date has been set for a trip to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Today's summit session was at <LOCATION> Daman-e-Koh </LOCATION>, a white-domed retreat on a hillside overlooking <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>. Police with rifles stood at intervals of 20 feet to 150 feet. Other uniformed and plainclothes guards stood in clusters, on rocky outcrops and among the trees and thickets. The security was a reminder of the region's potential for violence. Both <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and Sri Lankan President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> have escaped unhurt from assassination attempts in their capitals, while <LOCATION> Maldivian </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Maumoon </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gayoom </PERSON> was the target of an unsuccessful coup less than two months ago. Another participant, former Gen. <PERSON> Hussain </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, assumed power in a bloodless coup in 1982, although a yes-or-no referendum subsequently proclaimed him president. The other summit participants, King <PERSON> Birendra </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> and King <PERSON> Jigme </PERSON> <PERSON> Singhe </PERSON> <PERSON> Wangchuk </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bhutan </LOCATION>, rule through hereditary succession. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s avenue to power through popular election followed the death of President <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON>, who in 1977 overthrew her father, Prime Minister <PERSON> Zulfikar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> was subsequently convicted in a murder case and executed. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Raphel </PERSON> and 35 others were killed Aug. 17 in an explosion that destroyed their aircraft over <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Officials blamed sabotage but could not say who was responsible for downing the plane.
