<HEAD>China Calls for Direct Talks with Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senior <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> official today marked the 10th anniversary of a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> appeal for peaceful reunification with <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> by renewing <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s proposal for direct talks with <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s Nationalist government `` We hold that the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the Kumomintang -LRB- Nationalists -RRB- should establish contacts and start negotiations at an early date on the basis of equality,'' Vice Premier <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> <PERSON> Xueqian </PERSON> said. `` We can talk about the reunification of the country, or carry out consultations on the concrete issues concerning the relations between the two sides.'' <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> was speaking at a forum of 300 senior party and government leaders held to commemorate <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s `` message to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> compatriots'' issued on Jan. 1, 1979. The message called for the peaceful reunification of <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> with the mainland and proposed direct transportation and postal links as a first step toward easing tensions between the two nations. The official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, in a report on the forum, said the 1979 message signified a historic turning point in relations between the mainland and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has since then called for direct political and trade contacts and has said <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> can keep its current political and economic system if it rejoins the mainland. The Nationalists, who fled to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> after their defeat to the communists in 1949, have rejected all proposals for direct contacts with the mainland. However, in the past year the <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> government has eased travel and trade restrictions with the mainland. More than 400,000 <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> residents have traveled to the mainland in the past year, and indirect trade is estimated at $ 2.4 billion in 1988, up from $ 1.5 billion in 1987. `` Such changes are in accordance with people's wishes and the overall tendency of this historic development is therefore irreversible,'' <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> said. He also expressed concern about Taiwanese advocates of independence and those on the island who are in favor of `` two Chinas'' or `` dual recognition'' concepts. Reunification is in the interests of both sides, he said. `` This will not only help the whole country to quickly become prosperous, but will also help maintain sustained development on the island, which can then enjoy the prestige of the great motherland.''
