<FIRST>r i BC-Yugoslavia-Glance     12-30 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Yugoslavia-Glance,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yugoslavia At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some facts about <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE LAND _ <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> covers 98,766 square miles, slightly larger than <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. It a federation of six republics: <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, including the autonomous provinces of <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bosnia-Hercegovina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Macedonia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montenegro </LOCATION>. The capital is <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> occupies the western part of the <LOCATION> Balkan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION>, with a long coast on the <LOCATION> Adriatic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. About half the country is mountainous. A rich plain in the north and northeast, drained by the <LOCATION> Danube </LOCATION>, is the most fertile area. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is bordered by <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> in the north, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> in the east, and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION> in the south.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE PEOPLE _ <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s population of just over 23 million includes about 30 different nationalities. Serbs account for about 36 percent and the Croats for about 20 percent of the popoluation. Other Slav groups are the Slovenes, 8 percent; and the Montenegrins, 3 percent. Ethnic Albanians, who live mostly in the tense province of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, make up 9 percent of the population. An ethnic category known as Moslems accounts for another 9 percent. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s ethnic diversity has been a source of strife for centuries. The official languages are <LOCATION> Serbo-Croatian </LOCATION>, Slovene, and Macedonian. An estimated 41 percent of Yugoslavs are Orthodox, 32 percent Roman Catholics and 12 percent are Muslims.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE ECONOMY: After President <PERSON> Josip </PERSON> <PERSON> Broz </PERSON> <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>'s death in 1980, the economy has deteriorated sharply, revealing the shortcomings of the `` self-management'' system officially giving workers the say in running enterprises. In practice, Communist-dominated state planning and widespread corruption have caused serious problems. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> now has a $ 21 billion foreign debt, 250 percent inflation and 15 percent unemployment. Mounting worker discontent has led to more than 1,000 strikes in 1988.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 HISTORY: For about five centuries, much of the land that is modern <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> was under Ottoman rule, shaken off in 19th century uprisings. In December 1918, a Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes, including <LOCATION> Bosnia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hercegovina </LOCATION>, was formed. During World War II, the Nazi invaders were fought both by royalists and <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> partisans under <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>, who then became <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s undisputed postwar leader. <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> broke with Soviet dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> in 1948, and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> became a nonaligned communist country. Some of its present problems are attributed to the system bequeathed by Tito, including annual rotation of key offices and a weak federal authority. The state-run press and Yugoslavs themselves have become increasingly outspoken and liberal as the mounting social and economic problems have dented the authority of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
