<HEAD>Head of Police Auto Theft Unit Among 18 Indicted in Towing Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Six current or former police officers were among 18 people indicted in a towing scam that allegedly bilked at least 600 people from 1982 to 1987, authorities said. Police Sgt. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 51, chief of the department's auto theft unit, was charged with six counts of conspiracy, perjury and writing a false police report, according to indictments returned Thursday by a <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> grand jury The suspects allegedly participated in several schemes to tow legally and illegally parked cars and overcharge owners when they came to retrieve them, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON>, a spokesman for District Attorney <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON>. The grand jury handed up 1,500 charges in the indictments, which capped a two-year investigation. Police Commissioner <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> X. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roache </PERSON> vowed to continue probing police corruption. `` The public should be outraged that a group of people conspired to literally take 600 to 800 cars off the street with no authority, in total violation of the rules and regulations,'' he said. `` I think it's time to look at the whole towing industry.'' Also indicted were three other police officers, one <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> police officer, one former police captain, two employees of the city's abandoned car division, two former inspectors at the state Registry of Motor Vehicles, a special agent with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> and the owners of two city garages. The defendants face charges including larceny, concealing stolen motor vehicles, perjury, conspiracy and insurance fraud. <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> and Officer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cantin </PERSON>, 40, who was indicted on 535 charges, have been suspended without pay, police spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> said. Two other indicted officers, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Doherty </PERSON>, 47, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ulrich </PERSON>, 44, were placed on administrative leave pending a departmental hearing, <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON> said one alleged scheme profited from the different charges levied on cars towed by police and those towed by the <ORGANIZATION> Registry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vehicles </ORGANIZATION>, which charges more to drivers to retrieve cars. He said police would tow a car that was parked illegally but the defendants would tell the owner the car had been towed by the registry `` and pick up the extra money.'' Another scheme, <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON> said, would be to tow a legally parked car, and wait several weeks after the owner reported it stolen to collect daily storage charges _ often up to $ 600. The indictment does not say how much money was lost.
