<HEAD>Three Palestinians Killed, West Bank Schools Closed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israeli troops shot and killed three Palestinians in the occupied <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> over the last two days, the army said today. An army spokesman also said 1,194 Palestinian schools in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> will be shut for a week because of increased student violence. Two of the deaths in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> took place Thursday night in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> neighborhood of <LOCATION> Zeitoun </LOCATION>, the spokesman said. He said the two Palestinians were shot when they tried to escape after being ordered out of their house. The two were suspected of throwing firebombs, he said. `` They were ordered to come out,'' the spokesman said. `` Then they tried to escape and were shot.'' He said one suspect died at the scene, another died in an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> hospital and a third was captured unharmed. The violence continued today with one Palestinian killed and nine wounded in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> as army-imposed curfews confined at least 160,000 Palestinians to their homes in refugee camps and towns. An Arab reporter said the army broke up a protest that followed noon Moslem prayers in the Sheikh Radwan neighborhhod of <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. He said soldiers used clubs, rubber bullets and live ammunition. <PERSON> Abdel </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalim </PERSON> <PERSON> Behid </PERSON>, 22, was shot in the lung during the disturbance and died at <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Shifa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, hospital officials said. Five Arabs were wounded by gunshots, and a 4-year-old boy was hit in the head with a rubber bullet. The army confirmed Behid was killed by army gunfire, and that four Palestinians were wounded in the Sheikh Radwan clash. `` After prayers, they raised the Palestinian flag and threw stones,'' the army spokesman said. He said troops opened fire to disperse the crowd. Elsewhere in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, three Palestinians were wounded, among them a 35-year-old woman hit in the abdomen, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> doctors said. In the <LOCATION> Jabalya </LOCATION> refugee camp, a teenager was wounded. The deaths raised to at least 342 the number of Palestinians killed in the year-old rebellion against the 21-year occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Fourteen Israelis have also been killed. In the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s military administration announced a weeklong closure of all Palestinian schools because of `` numerous incidents of disturbances by students,'' a spokesman said. The measure, which takes effect Saturday, prevents about 300,000 Palestinian school students from attending classes. Schools in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> were closed by the army Feb. 3 for nearly 10 months. Authorities gradually reopened the 1,194 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> schools in December but made studies conditional on a halt to student violence. Army officials say schools often become focal points for violent demonstrations in the uprising. For that reason, four universities and 16 junior colleges in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> have been shut indefinitely. Palestinians have protested the closure, with educators arguing that students were losing the discipline for study.
