<HEAD>Right-Wing Official To Lose Car Rental Franchise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A car rental company said today it will take a franchise away from a member of a right-wing town council that has reinstated hard-line segregation laws. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Waal </PERSON>, executive director of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rent-a-Car </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement that his company would sever its ties in February with <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>, operator of a Budget franchise in <LOCATION> Brakpan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> is a member of the far-right <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which won control of councils in <LOCATION> Brakpan </LOCATION> and dozens of other towns in municipal elections on Oct. 26. The councils in <LOCATION> Brakpan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Boksburg </LOCATION>, both industrial towns on the eastern edge of the greater <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> region, have reinstated `` whites only'' status at parks and other public facilities that had been opened to all races in recent years. The actions have been widely condemned, not only by anti-apartheid groups but also by the government. However, the governing <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has given no indication it will repeal the Separate Amenities Act, which allows racial segregation of local facilities. `` We do not believe that Mr. <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>'s views and those of his <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> colleagues represent the outlook of the silent majority of <LOCATION> Brakpan </LOCATION> voters,'' said <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Waal </PERSON>. `` While the separate amenities legislation that is being enforced was put in place by the government, it appears these measures were dying an evolutionary death until the stance taken by the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.'' In another development, the Rev. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON>, a politician who has irked the government with his defiant tactics, says he has accepted an invitation to attend the inauguration of President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> told the annual congress of his <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday that he would attend the inauguration during a three-week trip to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He will miss the opening of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 1989 parliamentary session on Feb. 3. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> controls the mixed-race chamber of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, which also has chambers for whites and for Asians but excludes the black majority. Anti-apartheid activists criticized the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> for deciding to join the newly expanded <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in 1984, but in the past 18 months <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> has taken an increasingly confrontational stance toward the government. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
