<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An American Legion commander allegedly signed up 200 phony memberships, including a former German soldier and several dead people, to win a Recruiter of the Year award, a newspaper reported. Costa <ORGANIZATION> Mesa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> Cmdr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, who was named the state Legion's top recruiter in June, may have bought his way to the top, according to a report detailed in Thursday's editions of The Orange County Register. A three-member Legion committee issued its findings in a 13-page report signed Dec. 5 by state Cmdr. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Steffanic </PERSON>. The state <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legion </ORGANIZATION> awarded <ORGANIZATION> Hanson </ORGANIZATION> its Recruiter of the Year award at its <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> convention after <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> submitted 801 new memberships between July 1, 1987, and the 1988 convention. But the investigation found just 18 of the 801 applicants paid dues by check, while <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> wrote about 25 checks to the <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION> post for $ 8,250 from his own account. The report concluded, `` The question arises, was this an attempt to simply buy a large roster of members? If so, it would constitute an ominous attack on the integrity of The American Legion itself.'' It recommended charging <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> with violating the organization's rules by using `` unorthodox and erroneous'' recruiting methods <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> faces expulsion from the Legion, <PERSON> Steffanic </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, 67, declined to discuss the report. The investigation began after the Legion's national headquarters received inquiries from people wondering why they were receiving the American Legion Magazine. The report said one of the letters was from a disabled man who had never served in the