<HEAD>Search Expanded For Crew From Cargo Ship That Sank In Stormy Seas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf, `Two of ...' with memorial
today; Picks up 5th graf, `At first ...': DELETES now-outdated last
graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> expanded its search today for six crewmen missing from a Bermuda-bound container ship that sank in rough seas and gale-force winds in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, leaving two seamen dead. `` We continue the search as long as there's a chance of finding them alive,'' Coast Guard Petty Officer <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbogast </PERSON> said Thursday night. `` We have n't found the second life raft'' from the ship. Three crewmen were plucked from the sea Thursday after the 254-foot <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bermuda </ORGANIZATION> sank Wednesday night. A fourth was found dead and a fifth died on the way to the hospital. Two of the rescued men were transferred to the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> cutter <LOCATION> Tamaroa </LOCATION> and were helping searchers with information on what happened to their ship, <PERSON> Arbogast </PERSON> said. The victims were remembered at a ceremony today in <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, as friendly men who went out of their way to help others. The <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermuda </PERSON> had visited the port weekly. `` We are full of admiration for every one of the seafarers who have worked. ... We know how important the spirit of cooperation is to them,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Crafton </PERSON>, maritime chaplain and <LOCATION> Episcopal </LOCATION> priest. `` A seafarer is a brother to every other seafarer.'' At first light today, two <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> C-130 airplanes, one <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> C-130 airplane, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> P-3 Orion airplane, two <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> jets, two <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> helicopters and a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> helicopter joined the search, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petty </ORGANIZATION> Officer <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Scharlacken </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Lloyd </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> sank about 160 miles south of <LOCATION> Nantucket </LOCATION> and 200 miles east of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> when its cargo shifted in weather that was `` nothing short of horrendous,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>. <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said there was hope for the missing crewmen because the ship went down on the edge of the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stream </LOCATION>, where warm currents mix with frigid <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> waters. Two of the rescued crewmen did not suffer serious hypothermia. The ship's captain was American and the crew was a mix of nationalities, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Meyer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agencies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, the ship's agent in <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>, said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Hamilton </LOCATION> The <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermuda </PERSON>, registered in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, made a run to <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> every week, and had left <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, Tuesday night with a cargo including food and building materials, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said. Powerful winds hit the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> on Wednesday as a cold front moved swiftly through the area and out to sea. Around 7:10 p.m., the ship's cargo shifted. The captain issued a distress call, then called back a few minutes later to say he was abandoning ship, <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said. The ship capsized and began to sink within five minutes of the order to abandon ship, said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphreys </PERSON>, who spoke to one of the survivors. The men took to two life rafts. Rescuers began searching a 700-square-mile area for survivors but were hindered by heavy rains, 40 - to 45-mph winds and 25-foot seas Shortly after midnight Wednesday, a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> jet spotted three people in the water waving flashlights. Sailor aboard the merchant ship Eagle pulled two men from the water, but the third `` slipped from his life jacket, fell back into the water and was not seen again,'' <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said. The two survivors were treated for mild hypothermia. Around 4 a.m., a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> frogman from a helicopter rescued two men drifting in the water without life rafts. They were flown to <LOCATION> Falmouth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION>, but one man was pronounced dead, apparently of hypothermia, a hospital spokeswoman said. The other man, identified as <PERSON> Dario </PERSON> <PERSON> Macio-Lopez </PERSON>, 35, was treated for hypothermia, spokeswoman <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. At first light Thursday, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> pilot spotted what appeared to be a man waving from a life raft. But when rescuers reached the raft, they found nobody. Three hours later, rescuers spotted another man but, because of choppy seas and floating debris, could not get close enough to tell if he was alive. By the time a rescue helicopter reach