 A <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> native who came to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> almost 60 years ago said Friday he and his family had won their 13-year fight to leave, ending one of the most mixed-up Soviet emigration cases. <PERSON> Abe </PERSON> <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON>, his wife, <PERSON> Gita </PERSON>, and son, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, have been trying to emigrate since 1975. At one point in the battle, the family got as far as the entrance ramp of their plane when Soviet officials stopped them, claiming Mrs. <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> had access to state secrets in her job as a chemist in a geology institute. `` There's no feeling yet. It's just a big mess thinking of all the things we have to do,'' the 77-year-old <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON>, a Jew, said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` They drag it out so long. It's been 13 -LCB- years. The main thing now is to try to be calm and not to forget anything, which is hard.'' <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> and his family plan to go to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, but he said they did not know yet when they will leave. After settling in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, he said, the family will go to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to visit friends. Resolution of the case was another in a series of Soviet moves under <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to improve the country's human rights record. Many Jews who were refused permission for years have emigrated in the past year and a half. <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> came to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> as a teen-ager in 1931 with his parents, who were Russian emigres and ardent communists. His father died in <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s purges. <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> was disenchanted with the country to which he came to help build the first communist power, but he was stuck. <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> was called up to fight in the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> during World War II, where a Nazi grenade cost him the sight in his left eye. He later served as a translator and announcer for Radio <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> holds <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizenship, as does his son by virtue of <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON>'s birth and residence in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The family was stripped of its Soviet citizenship in 1975. That was when they were stopped at the entrance ramp of their plane. For 10 years the Soviets refused to let Mrs. <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> leave. Their belongings have remained in a warehouse in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> ever since. In the mid-1980s the family received final permission to leave, but <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> had a new problem. His son's new wife, <PERSON> Julia </PERSON>, is a Soviet citizen and her mother refused to sign a financial waiver allowing her to go. The family refused to leave without <PERSON> Julia </PERSON>, and mother and daughter have not been on speaking terms for many years. The <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> case has been high on the list of U.S.-Soviet human rights cases for years. Officials reported several times that it was solved, but new problems cropped up. `` I have news now,'' an excited <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> said, starting his telephone conversation. <PERSON> Julia </PERSON>, who has a 2 -LCB- - year-old daughter and an 8-month-old son, said in an interview that the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> told <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> officials about five days ago that her mother finally had signed a release allowing her to go She said she called the Soviet Visa and <ORGANIZATION> Registration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, OVIR, on Friday, and that Deputy Director <PERSON> Ilya </PERSON> <PERSON> Karakulkov </PERSON> had confirmed that officials received the signed waiver. She said she expects to receive official notification in the next several days. `` I'm sure there was pressure on my mother,'' <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> said. `` They called her into OVIR several times.'' She said she did not know why her mother finally signed the release and `` in no circumstances'' would call her to find out. She said many Jews remain behind in `` hopeless'' situations because their relatives refuse to sign waivers permitting them to emigrate. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, 29, said he had `` no special feelings.'' He said he worried about friends who want to emigrate but do n't have the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government on their side, like his family did. Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., who met with <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON>, credited <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> for the decision to allow <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> to return to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` I've worked on hundreds of Soviet emigration cases over the years, and this has been the toughest and the most frustrating,'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said from his home in <LOCATION> Makanda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> `` I do n't believe it would have been settled without President <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s direct involvement. It's also a hopeful sign about <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s struggle with his own bureaucracy. <PERSON> Abe </PERSON> <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> loves his hometown, and we're going to give him a grand tour when he comes back.'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hilton </LOCATION> has agreed to put <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> and his family up free of charge when he returns. <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> had told <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> a boyhood dream was to stay a night and `` live like a king'' in the old <ORGANIZATION> Steven </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION>, which is now the Hilton. <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> told <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>: `` We're trying to make plans. We just want to find a small quiet town, someplace green, no hurly-burly. I hope I can find work.''
