<HEAD>African Students Say Authorities Charge They Have AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NANKING, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Racial conflict between African and Chinese students was reported in another city Friday, and more than 60 Africans were sequestered in a dormitory to protest allegations by authorities that they have AIDS. The incident at the <ORGANIZATION> Zhejiang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hangzhou </LOCATION> took place against the backdrop of continued anti-black demonstrations in <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>, where Chinese students are demanding that African students involved in a Christmas Eve brawl be punished. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayuk </PERSON>, a student from <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION>, said the problems in <LOCATION> Hangzhou </LOCATION>, 143 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>, began Dec. 23 when a university operator started telling all incoming <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> callers to the foreign students dormitory that all African students were infected with AIDS. African students asked the university for an explanation but were not satisfied by a meeting with a university official, `` so we began our boycott,'' <PERSON> Ayuk </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Hangzhou </LOCATION>. On Wednesday, a school finance officer came to the dormitory and students locked him in the office of the gatekeeper, <PERSON> Ayuk </PERSON> said. The official escaped through a window at 5 a.m. Thursday after nine hours in captivity when the African students were asleep, he said. <PERSON> Ayuk </PERSON> said he believed the Chinese were prejudiced against all foreigners, but most strongly against Africans. He said the Africans had been given a nickname in <LOCATION> Hangzhou </LOCATION>: `` aizu bing,'' the Chinese words for AIDS. A student at the agricultural college from the <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION> was sent home in November after he tested positive for AIDS, but all the other African students have tested negative for the disease, <PERSON> Ayuk </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which has so far escaped the AIDS epidemic, requires all foreigners who live in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to undergo a test for acquired immune deficiency syndrome. An African student at <ORGANIZATION> Zhejiang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, also in <LOCATION> Hangzhou </LOCATION>, said police were not allowing other African students to leave the city. `` Today I wanted to go to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> but I was n't able,'' said <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Dujo </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION>. `` The police are preventing us from buying tickets.'' Another African said he believed the Chinese were using the fear of AIDS to restrict contact between Africans and Chinese. `` They ca n't stop the contact between us and the Chinese,'' said the student from <ORGANIZATION> Zhejiang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` We have many very good, deep friendships so what they're doing is using this to scare off the Chinese.'' <PERSON> Ayuk </PERSON> said hot water had been turned off in the dormitory and the canteen was closed. He said students were cooking in their rooms with what little food they had. There are an estimated 1,500 Africans from 40 nations studying at Chinese universities. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has long provided scholarships for Africans in a show of solidarity with developing African states, but social tensions, which Africans attribute to ingrained racial prejudices against blacks, have on occasion erupted into violent incidents between the Chinese and the Africans. In <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION> on Friday, about 140 African students continued to be held at a guest house of a chemical fiber factory outside the city. City authorities forced the Africans to the guest house Monday night, ostensibly to protect them from angry Chinese mobs. They have rejected the students' requests to leave <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>. During demonstrations Saturday and Sunday, thousands of Chinese threw rocks at African students and destroyed property in their dormitory rooms. The Chinese have demanded the Africans be brought to justice for allegedly starting a fight on Christmas Eve at <ORGANIZATION> Hehai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in which 11 Chinese were injured. <PERSON> Ye </PERSON> <PERSON> Chunsheng </PERSON>, vice director of the <ORGANIZATION> Jiangsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Provincial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>, said Friday the incident was under investigation and that about seven African students would be punished. He said the Africans were not cooperating in the investigation. `` They've locked their doors in the guest house and we ca n't get in to talk with them,'' he said. <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruiju </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Hehai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said on Thursday that no Chinese would be punished for the clash and subsequent anti-black demonstrations. As of Friday evening, the streets of <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION> were quiet for the first time since the initial clash Saturday. On Thursday, seven Africans and one student from <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> left the <ORGANIZATION> Nanking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polytechnical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> under police escort for the train station, where they traveled to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, said a student from the <LOCATION> Comoro </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. He would only identify himself by the name of <PERSON> Bourhane </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bourhane </PERSON> said the Africans, from <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION>, were not involved in the incident, but felt endangered in <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION> and wanted either to leave <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> or study in another city.
