<HEAD>Judge Blocks Government Plan to Put 9,000 Blacks In Homeland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge Friday blocked the government from proceeding with plans to place 9,000 rural blacks under the jurisdiction of a tribal homeland against their wishes. The ruling came hours after President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> issued a proclamation that the Braklaagte community would become part of the nominally independent homeland of <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION> on Saturday. <ORGANIZATION> Pretoria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> T.T. <PERSON> Spoelstra </PERSON> blocked immediate implementation of the proclamation and gave the government until March 7 to show why its plan should n't be invalidated. The leader of the Braklaagte community, Chief <PERSON> Pupsey </PERSON> <PERSON> Sebogodi </PERSON>, contended in court papers that his people faced hardship and discrimination if they were incorporated into <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION>. They live in a farming area about 100 miles west of <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. The community has voiced opposition in the past to the <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION> government and has sought to retain South African citizenship because of advantages in seeking employment. Residents feared that if they were incorporated into <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION>, they would be victimized unless they became citizens of the homeland. The intended incorporation was part of the government's longstanding and controversial policy of locating various black ethnic groups in self-governing or nominally independent homelands to reduce the proportion of blacks to whites in the rest of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> This policy suffered major defeats in court twice in 1988. The country's highest court, the Appeal Court, ruled in April that <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> acted without authority when he incorporated the 120,000-member community of <LOCATION> Moutse </LOCATION> into the adjoining, semi-autonomous homeland of <LOCATION> KwaNdebele </LOCATION>, northeast of <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. The incorporation provoked widespread violence in <LOCATION> Moutse </LOCATION>, where most residents do not belong to the <LOCATION> Ndebele </LOCATION> tribe that predominates in <LOCATION> KwaNdebele </LOCATION>. In August, the <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> provincial <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rejected a government plan to place <PERSON> Botshabelo </PERSON>, a vast black shantytown, under the jurisdiction of the Qwaqwa, an impoverished homeland 180 miles away. A three-judge panel said the merger would not promote the political development of <PERSON> Botshabelo </PERSON>'s estimated 500,000 residents. <PERSON> Zach </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Beer </PERSON>, leader of the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, criticized the attempt to excise Braklaagte from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` After the abject failure of the homelands policy during many years ... it is almost incredible that as 1989 opens, the government should yet again be forcing South Africans against their will to become inhabitants of one of these places,'' he said. <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION> is made up of seven separate pieces of territory in north-central <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. It has an estimated 1.7 million residents and covers 18,000 square miles. Under apartheid, the 26 million blacks in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
