<HEAD>Japan Gets Second Justice Minister This Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> appointed his second justice minister of the week Friday as his scandal-buffeted government lurched toward the end of what commentators are calling a gloomy year in Japanese politics. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> had to reach outside the world of politics to name a new justice minister, picking <PERSON> Masami </PERSON> <PERSON> Takatsuji </PERSON>, 78, a former <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justice with experience in drafting legislation as a bureaucrat in the 1960s and 1970s. On Tuesday the prime minister appointed <PERSON> Takashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON>, a 76-year-old member of parliament, to the justice portfolio. But <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON> lasted only 60 hours _ said to be a postwar record for short <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> tenure _ as it became known he had received donations for years from <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> is investigating on suspicion of bribery. At the root of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s political gloom is the scandal involving the Recruit conglomerate, whose founder sold unlisted shares of a subsidiary at bargain prices to politicians, their aides and business leaders. The share prices more than doubled when they were publicly listed in 1986, and the holders made fat, tax-free profits when they sold. The Recruit scandal has been dubbed the top story of the year by Japanese media, rivaled only by the similarly downbeat story of the illness of Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, 87, who has been bedridden with intestinal hemorrhaging since Sept. 19. `` The year 1988 was an indescribably gloomy one for Japanese politics, and one that calls for much soul-searching,'' commentator <PERSON> Minoru </PERSON> <PERSON> Tada </PERSON> wrote in Friday's <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> Times. He said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s leadership `` is deeply tainted by money power. An editorial Friday in the <ORGANIZATION> Asahi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SHimbun </ORGANIZATION>, another newspaper, said the just-concluded session of parliament `` showed Japanese politics at its ugliest and most corrupt.'' As <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON> gave up the justice portfolio Friday, some opposition leaders and analysts said <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> should resign his entire government and call elections. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, who had appointed <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON> Tuesday along with a new Cabinet in a drive to restore public confidence in government, did not immediately comment on the major setback. Instead, the outgoing and incoming justice ministers spoke to reporters. <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON> apologized and said he had n't known until Wednesday that Recruit had been giving money to his political support organization since 1976. `` However, as minister in charge of clearing up the Recruit problem in the <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> administration, which is trying to heighten trust in government, it is regrettable that I received donations from Recruit,'' he said. The scandal now has brought the resignations of 18 public figures _ including two <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> members _ since it hit the front pages last summer. Business leaders, top bureaucrats and news media executives are among the casualties. After <PERSON> Hasegawa </PERSON>'s donations from Recruit became known, three other members of the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> also said the company had donated to them, making it apparent that <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> would have to go outside his <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to find a justice minister untainted by Recruit money. <PERSON> Takatsuji </PERSON>, who served on the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> from 1973 to 1980, said he had no connection at all to the Recruit firm. `` I do n't really have anything to say about Recruit,'' <PERSON> Takatsuji </PERSON> said. `` My attitude toward it is no different from that of the people in general.'' Public approval of <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s government has slumped badly since he became prime minister in November 1987. A <ORGANIZATION> Mainichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION> newspaper poll in December showed his approval had dropped from 30 percent to 18 percent, and a <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> poll showed his approval rating down to 35.9 percent from 54.8 percent three months earlier. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> himself has a Recruit link since an aide and a relative profited from shares in the <ORGANIZATION> Recruit-Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, but he says he was not personally involved. His popularity also has suffered from the railroading of a controversial tax reform through the Diet, or parliament. Some analysts expect <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> will face further setbacks if there are arrests in the Recruit affair and as the opposition uses the scandal to try to block passage of the budget in the Diet. `` Since <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> had advocated the importance of public consensus ... he and his administration should resign as public support goes lower,'' said <PERSON> Masayuki </PERSON> <PERSON> Fukuoka </PERSON>, a political science professor at <ORGANIZATION> Komazawa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Despite the polls, many analysts think the Japanese are inured to shady practices under the governing conservatives, who have held power for all the postwar years except for 10 months in 1947-48. `` The Japanese take it for granted,'' said <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalera </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think they may be rather blase about this.'' The pervasiveness of shady money was shown in a report issued Friday by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, which estimated that Japanese firms had spent $ 456 million in 1987 on such `` shady expenses'' as illegal political donations and back-door rebates to other firms. The figure was a record, up 24 percent from the previous high in 1984, the agency said.
