<HEAD>Government Works On Comprehensive Economic Recovery Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The new government, grappling with its first crisis, has begun work on an economic program aimed at restoring public confidence in the shekel and ending a speculative run on the dollar. Finance Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> was expected to ask the Cabinet on Sunday to approve the outlines of an economic recovery plan that will be the most comprehensive since the emergency anti-inflation program of 1985, analysts said. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio reported Friday that <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> was considering a $ 600 million cut in government spending, an increase in fees for government services, a reduction in subsidies for food and other necessities, and an end to automatic cost-of-living salary increases for workers. The Cabinet also was expected to approve a further devaluation of the shekel, perhaps as much as 10 percent, the radio said. The new government, a coalition of the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc and the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> that is similar to the previous government, was installed Dec. 22. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, is the former foreign minister. The government has spent the past week trying to stem a massive buying binge of foreign currencies by the public and large financial institutions. The <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's central bank, on Tuesday devalued the shekel 5 percent by adjusting the exchange rate to 1.680 shekels to the dollar from 1.599 shekels. On Friday, the central bank halted all foreign currency trading to stop further speculative buying. The markets are expected to reopen Tuesday after the New Year's holiday. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON>, the bank's governor, predicted on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio that once the new economic program is adopted, `` the public will calm down and the markets will stabilize.'' In the three days before trading was stopped, Israelis responded to rumors of an impending devaluation by purchasing $ 285 million worth of foreign currencies, mostly dollars. They apparently hope to sell at a profit after the shekel is devalued. The Israeli economy faces other major problems, including an industrial slump, rising budget deficits and inflation approaching 20 percent a year. <PERSON> Efran </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleiman </PERSON>, chairman of the economics department at <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, noted that when the government introduced its last emergency program in July 1985, prices were rising at an annual rate of 440 percent or more. `` We do n't have hyper-inflation anymore,'' he said. `` But the government's idea now is the same _ not to do things unilaterally but to get some kind of agreement, a social contract.'' This will require support from <ORGANIZATION> Histadrut </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's massive labor federation, which represents about 80 percent of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s workforce But Histadrut General-Secretary <PERSON> Yisrael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kessar </PERSON> said Friday that workers ca n't be expected to relinquish their cost-of-living guarantee unless they are assured of other compensation. Union workers now get automatic pay increases equal to about 70 percent of the inflation rate. But he added, `` This does n't mean we do n't want to be partners in a comprehensive plan.''
