<HEAD>Security, Terrorists in Technological `Arms Race'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf with 2 grafs to CORRECT that El Al has had a
hijacking.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Air terrorism has spawned a grisly `` arms race'' between the security establishment and the ever-increasing sophistication of the terrorist arsenal. As bomb-detection machinery has grown more refined, explosives have become easier to conceal. As one security gap closes, terrorists find another. Because of lack of personnel and the expense of operating X-ray equipment, `` we are always at least two steps behind the terrorists,'' <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Orrell </PERSON> of the British flight engineers' union said Friday, eight days after a bomb blew up <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, killing all 259 people aboard and leaving 11 on the ground missing and presumed dead. But other experts say the quest for terrorist-proof air travel has reached an outer limit beyond which it will become prohibitively expensive or make flying unbearably uncomfortable. When air terrorism became a problem in the late 1960s, authorities responded by transforming airports into fortresses. It now is routine for all passengers to go through metal detectors while their hand luggage is X-rayed. Airlines especially at risk, such as <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Al </ORGANIZATION>, search all luggage by hand. At <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> airports, the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> terrorist threat makes it necessary to frisk not just the passengers but everyone else coming into the terminal. Airlines insist that each piece of luggage match its passenger, assuming that no bomber would travel aboard the targeted plane. So terrorists have resorted to duping unwitting passengers into carrying explosives onto planes. Passengers are regularly warned to accept no baggage they have n't packed themselves. The search for suspicious objects has become much harder with the advent of plastic explosives that give off virtually no detectable odor. They are malleable enough to be shaped into a souvenir or rolled wafer-thin to fit inside a suitcase lining. Detonators now are small enough to fit into a suitcase lock. Moreover, the age of the metal-free handgun is looming. According to <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyd </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, such a gun has been developed in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and will be extremely hard to detect on X-ray screens. `` The sophistication and miniaturization of explosives has become quite worrisome,'' <PERSON> Kyd </PERSON> said in an interview. According to <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Learmount </PERSON> of the respected journal Flight International: `` It's an arms race.'' Bombs can be connected to barometric detonators that respond to altitude changes. Airports have hit back by putting baggage through simulated pressure to set off such bombs in safety. The terrorists, in turn, have come up with a double-device: the pressure detonator goes off safely, but it activates a second timer that will detonate the bomb in the air. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that this method was believed to have been used on Flight 103. <PERSON> Kyd </PERSON> is optimistic that within two years, a highly advanced explosives detector will become operational. Now being tested in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> laboratories, the machine bombards objects with thermoneutron rays that detect telltale nitrogen vapors. But to cover the vast amount of baggage moving through large airports, it will have to be small, mobile and able to distinguish explosives' vapors from those given off by aviation fuel, said <PERSON> Kyd </PERSON>. He said the biggest security hole now lies not in the terminals where passengers arrive to catch flights but on the tarmac where the planes are parked. Security, he said, is difficult to impose on the hundreds of airport workers swarming about the tarmac. Many of the menial jobs are held by low-paid immigrants who are vulnerable to bribery and whose background is unverifiable in a security screening. `` We can put all the screens in place to check passengers and luggage, but there's still the problem of direct access to aircraft by people who are there to clean planes, fuel them and put food aboard,'' he said. The weapons used in the hijacking of a Kuwaiti airliner by Iranian extremists this year were probably smuggled aboard in catering trolleys in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kyd </PERSON> said. `` A huge amount can still be done for security, but the fact that it's possible does n't mean it's feasible,'' <PERSON> Learmount </PERSON> said in an interview. <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Al </PERSON> is unique, he said, because `` <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as a nation operates in some respects under siege, under military conditions, and all its citizens accept that. So its airline has to act in many respects like a military operation.'' El Al passengers have to check in three hours before takeoff, their baggage is hand-searched, and the slightest irregularity in a travel document can mean a polite but lengthy interrogation about the passenger's origins, work, family, friends and purpose of travel. If another airline used such tactics on passengers, <PERSON> Learmount </PERSON> said, `` I suspect they would n't keep on flying with you for very long.'' <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Al </PERSON> has never had an aircraft bombed. But an <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Al </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 707 was hijacked over Italian airspace by three armed members of the <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> on July 23, 1968. All passengers and crew were freed over several days after the plane landed in <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
