<HEAD>Bhutto, Ghandi Hit It Off, Sources Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> and Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, the offspring of leaders who helped feed the bitter feud between their nations, were `` getting along famously'' on Friday, sources said. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, who took office four weeks ago, met <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> for the first time Thursday when he arrived in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> for a seven-nation <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> summit that has been overshadowed by meetings between the leaders of the region's two mightiest powers. The two held a second private meeting Friday, and Indian sources said the talks were friendly and productive. `` Their talks have been very warm, very cordial,'' an Indian official said, speaking on condition of anonymity. He said there was hope for `` a new face on the relationship between the two countries, one of warmth, trust and confidence.'' Another Indian source said: `` They're getting along famously.'' Pakistani officials declined comment on the talks. Before <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> returns to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> on Saturday, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> are expected to sign three agreements, including one in which the countries agree not to attack each other's nuclear installations, Indian sources said. The others provide for cultural exchanges and an end to double taxation in trade and commerce. The signings appear to be largely symbolic and designed to emphasize hopes that new leadership in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> will lead to better relations with <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. The cultural and taxation agreements were initialed about a year ago by both countries. A verbal agreement on the nuclear non-attack pact was reached three years ago during a visit to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> by President <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON>, the army general who overthrew Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s father, Prime Minister <PERSON> Zulfikar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, in 1977. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> was subsequently executed after being convicted of what he said was a trumped-up charge of conspiracy to murder a political opponent. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> was among those killed Aug. 17 in an explosion that destroyed an aircraft over <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s first private meeting began at 9 p.m. Thursday and lasted until 1:30 a.m., Indian sources say. The only other people present were Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s husband, businessman <PERSON> Asif </PERSON> <PERSON> Zardari </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Sonia </PERSON>. On Friday, the Indian and Pakistani prime ministers attended an all-day session with the leaders of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bhutan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Maldives </LOCATION> as part of the fourth annual summit of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> then met again for more than two hours. They were joined midway through the meeting by their foreign ministers, <PERSON> Narasimha </PERSON> <PERSON> Rao </PERSON> of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Yaqub </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The talks `` covered the whole gamut'' of problems between the nations, including disputes in <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, the Indian official said. In the last five years, <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> has been the scene of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s worst violence More than 2,400 people were killed in the border state this year by Sikh separatists. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> claims <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> aids the extremists. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> denies this. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s mother and immediate predecessor, Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, was killed by two of her Sikh bodyguards in October 1984, four months after she ordered an army raid on the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>, where Sikh militants were holed up. More than 2,000 people, mostly Sikhs, were killed. The <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> border dispute dates back to 1947 when Moslem <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Hindu </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> were partitioned along religious lines. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> claims a portion of the region lying in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The Indian official declined to give any details of Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s discussions, but said the leaders did more than outline problems but discussed `` what we will be able to do about them.'' <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> is to meet again with Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> on Saturday. Other participants in the summit are President <PERSON> Hussain </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Maymoon </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gayoom </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Maldives </LOCATION>, King <PERSON> Birendra </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> and King <PERSON> Jigme </PERSON> <PERSON> Singhe </PERSON> <PERSON> Wangchuk </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bhutan </LOCATION>.
