<HEAD>FHA Begins Loan Program For Businesses Affected By Drought</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it will begin next week a $ 200 million loan guarantee program for rural businesses that suffered from the 1988 drought and other weather disasters. Acting FmHA administrator <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Verne </PERSON> <PERSON> Ausman </PERSON> said the program was authorized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the 1988 Disaster Assistance Act. New regulations carrying out the program will be put into effect on Jan. 3, although they will have a 60-day period for public comment. <PERSON> Ausman </PERSON> said the agency `` can make any changes that may be necessary after the 60-day comment period is over.'' Meanwhile, he said, many rural businesses are in need of assistance. The maximum loan amount is $ 500,000. Under the program, FmHA can guarantee up to 90 percent of a loan `` to help alleviate financial distress caused, directly or indirectly, by drought, hail, excessive moisture or related conditions'' that occurred in 1988, he said. The program will be similar in most respects to the existing FmHA business and industrial, or B & amp; I, guaranteed loans. The loans will be made by regular commercial lenders at negotiated interest rates, with <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION> guarantees providing protection against loss should the loans fail. <PERSON> Ausman </PERSON> said the main difference is that the drought and disaster program will guarantee only the principal, while the <ORGANIZATION> B </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; I program guarantees both principal and interest.
