<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia, Bjt,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Resigns, Major Changes Not Forseen</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY24; LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government resigned Friday in reaction to mounting criticism of its handling of an economic crisis, the first to do so since the communists took power after World War II. The move, a sign of the liberalization creeping into <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s one-party system, represented a further break with the legacy of President <PERSON> Josip </PERSON> <PERSON> Broz </PERSON> <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>, founder of communist <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> and its undisputed leader until his death in 1980 Premier <PERSON> Branko </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> he and the entire 31-member Cabinet stepped down because legislators refused Wednesday to pass an economic law needed to ensure continued support from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. Mikulic, a 60-year-old economist and <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> ally who took office in May 1986, was seen as a hardliner in the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. His resignation indicated that reform-oriented forces eager to adopt Western-style changes are gaining the upper hand in a protracted political struggle. Few Yugoslavs, however, expected <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON>'s resignation to bring any immediate solutions to an economic crisis that has reduced living standards by 50 percent since 1980. Foreign debt stands at $ 21 billion, unemployment at 15 percent and inflation at around 250 percent _ three times what it was when <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON> took office. In a speech to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> broadcast on live national television, <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON> firmly rejected responsibility for the country's economic and social woes. Effectively blaming the system bequeathed by <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>, he said difficulties created in past decades could not be solved in the 2 -LCB- years he has spent in office. Mikulic will stay in office as a caretaker premier until the nine-man federal presidency names a new government in January. The complex federal system bequeathed by <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> stipulates that all federal decisions must be unanimously agreed on by <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six constituent republics and two autonomous provinces. In practice, this has meant that federal decisions are watered down to ineffectual compromises that each region interprets as it wants. Referring to <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s maze of federal, <ORGANIZATION> republican </ORGANIZATION> and local bureaucracies and laws, <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> that decisions about the economy are made in 7,000 to 8,000 different places, suggesting it was unfair to blame the government. Falling living standards have provoked more than 1,000 strikes this year in a country once hailed as a worker-managed state. Discontent also has eaten at the prestige of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, whose membership has fallen steadily. Two <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> residents who asked not to be named said they expected little to change after the first fall of a Communist government in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. `` Did they fall indeed?'' a travel agent asked upon being told the news. `` So who is going to congratulate us -LRB- for -RRB- the New Year?'' she quipped. A housewife shopping before the three-day New Year holiday lamented the difficulty of making ends meet each month. `` So what do you expect will happen now?,'' she said. `` They are all of a kind. They can not do anything, or do not want to, except build seaside villas at the expense of the workers.'' She was referring to a scandal in <LOCATION> Mikulic </LOCATION>'s native republic of <LOCATION> Bosnia-Hercegovina </LOCATION>, where hundreds of party officials have been accused of securing illegal loans to build themselves homes in the Adriatic resort of Neum. <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON> survived an attempted vote of confidence in May, when parliamentary deputies from the liberal northern republic of <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> and from <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION> failed to gain support from four other republics for <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON>'s ouster. But criticism had mounted in recent weeks. Government minister <PERSON> Oskar </PERSON> <PERSON> Kovac </PERSON>, who oversaw <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s negotiations with its debtors, resigned Dec. 5, citing unidentified pressures that hindered market-oriented reform. Ironically, parliament on Thursday passed a package of economic reform laws that should allow mixed ownership and greater foreign investment _ measures economists have long prescribed for <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s economic ills. Increasing poverty has exacerbated traditional ethnic conflicts among the more than 30 ethnic groups who make up <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s 23 million citizens. But parliament on Wednesday defied <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON>'s warnings about the need to live up to its obligations to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, refusing to pass a law curbing public spending. Such austerity measures are a condition of <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> aid to inflation-ridden countries such as <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> had demanded the law as a condition for granting the <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> government a one-year, $ 416 million standby credit in June. Some $ 260 million of that credit has been used to date, according to official estimates. The loan also encouraged Western creditors to reschedule payments on <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s mounting foreign debt.
