<HEAD>Beekeeper, Rothschild Honored by the Queen</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed For Release 7:01 p.m. EST _ Time Set By Source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUDREY WOODS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From a beekeeper and a mailman to a Rothschild and three Olympic gold medalists, the humble and the powerful were rewarded Saturday for good works and political loyalty in that grand old British tradition, the queen's New Year honors list. Sculptor <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Paolozzi </PERSON> is knighted, as is <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Brittan </PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> secretary who resigned in controversy in 1986. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Holroyd </PERSON>, biographer of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>, becomes a Commander of the Order of the British Empire, as do actor <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogwood </PERSON>, director of the Academy of Ancient Music. Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> bestowed 907 titles and medals _ most of them to people selected by Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s government for the twice-yearly expression o gratitude. They will be joined in June by hundreds more from the queen's birthday list. Although critics say the ancient honors tradition has been tarnished by political patronage, a barony, a knighthood or a British Empire Medal is still a glittering prize to be treasured for life and remembered with pride by one's descendents. Barons and baronesses are addressed as lords and ladies and can sit in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s unelected <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lords </ORGANIZATION> in the company of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s ancient aristocratic families. Knights are addressed as sir, and their female equivalents are dames. An Officer of the Order of the British Empire gets to add OBE after his or her name. There is no cash reward but to many the rise in status is priceless. For the public at large, it is an occasion to reflect on heroes both sung and unsung, like <PERSON> Domingos </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Diago </PERSON> <PERSON> Teodoro </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinto </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> doctor got an OBE for leading the medical team that treated casualties in an Irish <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> bombing that killed eight soldiers. This power to pander to vanity prompts accusations _ firmly denied _ that prime ministers use the honors to repay political cronies and party fund donors. Political loyalty is warmly rewarded each year. <PERSON> Brittan </PERSON>, awarded a knighthood, was a close Cabinet ally of Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> before he resigned for approving the leak of a controversial letter during a government crisis. He is now one of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s two commissioners on the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s administrative body. The government, underlining Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s new commitment to conservation, recommended honors for several guardians of the environment this year. The highest goes to <ORGANIZATION> Cambridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> chemistry professor <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, who chaired a commission on environmental pollution. He becomes a life baron. <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothschild </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> N.M. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rothschild </ORGANIZATION> and Sons and member of the British branch of the illustrious banking family, becomes a knight, as does <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>, editor of the respected <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. Following the peerages and knighthoods, the highest honors belong to the Order of the British Empire and its Commanders -LRB- CBE -RRB-, Officers -LRB- OBE -RRB-, and Members -LRB- MBE -RRB-. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> McIntyre </PERSON> and <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Vaile </PERSON>, yachting gold medalists at the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Olympics, receive MBEs, while <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodds </PERSON>, captain of the gold-medal-winning hockey team gets an OBE. An OBE goes to <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Littlewood </PERSON>, 57, who masterminded the four-year reconstruction of the badly burned south transept of York Minster, the medieval cathedral where his family has worked for three generations. <PERSON> Littlewood </PERSON> supervised the craftsmen who worked in stone, wood and stained glass and the queen celebrated the completed work this year, 12 months ahead of schedule. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooper </PERSON>, vice-chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beekeeping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> becomes one of 306 new MBEs. <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Quantrill </PERSON>, postman, wins a British Empire Medal. An MBE also goes to darts champ <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Bristow </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s most recognizable sportsmen The rotund `` Crafty Cockney,'' reckoned the greatest darts player in history, becomes the first in his field to win such an honor. Actress <PERSON> Penelope </PERSON> <PERSON> Keith </PERSON>, known to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> TV audiences for her role in `` To The Manor Born'' and `` The Good Neighbors,'' and actor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Briers </PERSON>, who also appeared in `` The Good Neighbors,'' receive OBEs, as does horror film actor <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cushing </PERSON>. <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, honored with a CBE, portrayed spy <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Blunt </PERSON> in the BBC-TV play `` Anthony Blunt'' in addition to many film and stage roles.
