<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Reform, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0592,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reformers Decry `Dictatorship of Mediocrity'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf with 1 graf to ADD another signer of letter;
picks up 8th graf pvs: ``Speeches by...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Churbanov, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leading supporters of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms said in a letter published Friday that his policies are being bogged down by a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> `` dictatorship of mediocrity'' that ought to resign. Six artists, directors and editors, in an open letter to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, said elections for a new government structure, a <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, will determine real power in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. They pledged all-out support for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. But they said that a campaign begun after the June party conference in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to review nearly 20 million party members with a view toward their support for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms had been hampered by too many directives. They said that experience made them doubt whether the elections would firmly implant reformers throughout the Soviet system. `` Can it be said that we are entering the new year and moving toward elections with full confidence in the irreversibility of the democratic renewal of society?'' they asked. `` One would very much like to answer that question positively. But a feeling of sensible, realistic responsibility holds us back from such an evaluation.'' The writers said a `` dictatorship of mediocrity'' was rampant, not only among individual conservatives who remain in the party apparatus, but throughout the entire <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. The letter was published in the Jan. 1 edition of the weekly <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, which was released Friday. It was signed by <PERSON> Grigory </PERSON> <PERSON> Baklanov </PERSON>, editor of the monthly literary journal <LOCATION> Znamya </LOCATION>; playwright <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Gelman </PERSON>; author <PERSON> Danil </PERSON> <PERSON> Granin </PERSON>; film producer <PERSON> Elem </PERSON> <PERSON> Klimov </PERSON>, actor <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Ulyanov </PERSON>; and space scientist <PERSON> Roald </PERSON> <PERSON> Sagdeyev </PERSON>. Speeches by <PERSON> Baklanov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ulyanov </PERSON> both caused sharp disputes with conservatives at the June party conference. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has sought to get the party out of day-to-day management, leaving that to local economic and government officials. But the party retains final authority and has shown no sign of tolerating any opposition. The writers said that there undoubtedly must be opponents of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> society, and that they must be able to state their ideas. But it said party members who oppose <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms must be judged severely `` Those who do not agree with the new course must retire,'' they said. The six also appealed for more tolerance of informal political and social organizations that have sprung up in the freer atmosphere fostered by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms. `` If we do n't find the path toward cooperation with dissidents, a temptation to rush to repressive measures probably will arise _ and already has arisen _ with all the anti-democratic consequences that flow from this,'' they said. Cooperation with dissidents `` not only does n't weaken, but on the contrary, strengthens the authority of restructuring'' they said.
