 <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> on Friday offered to send experts to help identify explosives that blew up <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 following reports a Czech-manufactured explosive may have been used. A <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> statement categorically denied that <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> ever provided explosives to terrorists. British authorities said Wednesday that the residue of explosives recovered from the debris of the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 that crashed in <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, on Dec. 21, was `` consistent with the use of a high-performance plastic explosive.'' That led to speculation the bomb may have been made of Semtex, an orange-colored plastic explosive manufactured in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. Terrorism experts and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials have said that <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> obtained Semtex from <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and passed it on to surrogate terrorist groups. So far, no group or individual has been identified as a prime suspect in the bombing. `` <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> again emphasizes that it condemns categorically all acts, forms and methods of terrorism and that it complies consistently with the appropriate international commitments,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> statement, carried by the state news agency <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION>. `` It has never supplied and does not supply explosions to terrorist organizations,'' the statement said. <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> said the Ministry issued the statement in response to reports Semtex may have been used in the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ