<HEAD>Increased Meat Imports Not Expected To Trigger Quotas Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Meat imports are not expected to rise enough in 1989 to trigger mandatory quotas on shipments from foreign suppliers, <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said Friday. The annual estimate is required by law and is subject to revision every three months during the calendar year. It was the first estimate for 1989. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said a formula in the law calls for maximum imports of slightly less than 1.438 billion pounds in 1989, down 87.7 million pounds from the 1988 trigger level. But <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said total 1989 imports are not expected to exceed 1.425 billion pounds, or about 13 million pounds below the quota trigger. The law covers imports of fresh, chilled or frozen meat of cattle, sheep -LRB- except lambs -RRB- and goats, and certain prepared and preserved beef and veal products. Most is low-grade beef used to make hamburger and other processed meat items. <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> are the principal suppliers, although about a dozen countries are eligible to ship quota-type meat into the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market.
