 It has been 11 years since <ORGANIZATION> Craig </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> furled its flag in the nation's last round of military-base closings, a blow the mayor says hurt <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION> more than the tumultuous civil rights era. In just one day _ Oct. 1, 1977 _ the city and surrounding <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> lost 2,500 military and civilian jobs, a $ 40 million payroll and untold millions in economic spinoffs, the kind of fiscal future other communities may face under the list of 34 recommended base closings released Thursday by a government panel. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Smitherman </PERSON>, mayor of <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION> then and now, said Friday that gains have been made in converting the former flight-training base to private use. But the mostly black, rural area still has not recovered, he said. `` We have n't got it developed like we hoped it would be. It's mostly turned into a housing project,'' <PERSON> Smitherman </PERSON> said While the nation remembers <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION> for civil rights benchmarks like the Bloody Sunday clash on the Edmund Pettus Bridge and the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s subsequent voting rights march to <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> in 1965, <PERSON> Smitherman </PERSON> said the loss of <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> was `` the biggest single impact ... we've had on the area.'' `` People do adjust to civil rights changes. But it's hard to adjust to an economic loss like the base,'' he said. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, head of the authority that oversees what used to be the base, said <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s unemployment rate temporarily doubled to about 20 percent when <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> shut down. `` But it was a lot more than that. There was the real estate. And people who were used to having a lot of military business lost it,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>. State statistics showed <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s unemployment rate at 8.6 percent in 1976, the last full year of record-keeping before the closing. The rate rose to 9.3 percent in 1979, but that number reflects only the number of residents seeking employment. Rather than try to find work in the county, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> estimates that 3,000 to 3,700 people out of a town of 27,000 simply left. In the decade since <PERSON> Craig </PERSON>'s closure, local authorities have fought tooth-and-nail over the field, <PERSON> Smitherman </PERSON> said. `` We got word one time that -LRB- federal officials -RRB- were considering putting Cuban prisoners out here. We stopped that. The state prison people were going to put a minimum-security prison out here, and we stopped that,'' he said. What does exist at <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> is a municipal airport, a training school for state police officers and prison guards, several companies, warehouses and housing. While as many as 700 people worked at <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> two years ago, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said the recent closing of a Beechcraft Aircraft plant reduced that number to 275 to 300. Of the 500 military housing units on the property, the federal government controls 50, the <LOCATION> Craig </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> sold about 50, about 330 are rented and 70 remain vacant, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> had some advice for communities that stand to lose military facilities under the panel's recommendations: `` They need to go after that property. I think you need to plan your work and then work your plan.''
