<HEAD>Marshall Plan Architect Dies At 93</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaisdell </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, recognized as one of the key designers of the Marshall Plan that restored a devastated <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> after World War II, has died at the age of 93. <PERSON> Blaisdell </PERSON>, who died Tuesday, was a distinguished professor of political science at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California-Berkeley </ORGANIZATION> who continued teaching long after assuming emeritus status in 1963. A native of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Blaisdell </PERSON> joined the administration of President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> in 1933, where he worked on the Consumer's <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and in the Agricultural Adjustment Administration. Over the next two decades, he held a number of federal positions, working first on helping the nation recover from the Depression and then on European post-war reconstruction. <PERSON> Blaisdell </PERSON> was assistant secretary of commerce during the administration of President <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>, and it was from hat office that he became the man many colleagues described as the principal designer of the Marshall Plan. <PERSON> Blaisdell </PERSON> earned a bachelor's degree at <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in 1916. He did postgraduate work at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, earning a master's degree in social history in 1922 and a doctorate in 1932. He taught at <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> from 1925 to 1932. He joined the <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> faculty in 1951. A frequent author, perhaps his best-known work was published in 1976. The book, `` The American Presidency in Political Carto