<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a year-end message to the nation Friday, President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> announced a 10 percent increase in the minimum legal salary of $ 57 a month earned by nearly one third of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s 4 million workers. The 73-year-old president and army commander said in a speech over national radio and TV that a 10 percent wage increase also will be granted to <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s 500,000 government workers, with both increases effective Feb. 1. He said the wage increases were made possible by the `` economic equilibrium and the firm economic growth'' achieved by his 15-year-old military government. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> asked Chileans to unite to face `` the important challenges that we will meet in the new year.'' He said `` national unity'' is his government's main goal. `` Let's set aside those things that separate us,'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> said. `` Let's firmly fight those who want to destroy our national soul, and let's form a united front with the single aim of serving <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> and Chileans, and make of our motherland a great country.'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who came to power following a 1973 coup, was defeated in an Oct. 5 referendum in which he sought to remain in power until 1997. As a result, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> was forced to call open presidential and congressional elections, now scheduled for Dec. 14, 1989. He expressed hope that the election will `` consolidate the type of society'' sought by his government.
