<HEAD>Demonstrations Continue Despite Price Concessions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to RESTORE first reference to reporter
Mohamed Osman. Pickup 5th graf `Dispatches received...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. MANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anti-government protesters took to the streets of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> and other cities in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> for a fourth day Friday despite government concessions on food price increases. At least two people were reported killed. A Western diplomat reported rumors of an imminent coup attempt in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> and said the East African country remained paralyzed by a general strike. Communications were still disrupted. <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Fatih </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdoun </PERSON>, the capital's head of government, told <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> reporter <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> that `` an unidentified gunman opened fire on demonstrators'' outside Cabinet offices on Thursday, killing two and wounding 28. <PERSON> Osman </PERSON>, speaking by radio from <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, also reported one dead and 21 injured, including some victims from outside <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> in eastern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. It was not known whether the victims were included in the previous report. Dispatches received in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> from the Egyptian and <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> news agencies on Thursday reported what appeared to be two separate shooting incidents, including one after dark with `` intensive shooting'' near government headquarters. There were no reports of new violence Friday. But a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat in the Ethiopian capital, <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>, reported `` complete political chaos'' in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. The diplomat, who watches Sudanese affairs and said he was in contact with <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, said the disturbances `` do not seem to have subsided, despite the fact that the price increases which originally sparked the trouble have been rolled back.'' `` The action in the streets is taking on a definite anti-government flavor,'' he said. `` It looks like the government is in serious trouble. There's a lot of talk about a coup attempt coming out of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>.'' Thousands of Sudanese began demonstrations and strikes Tuesday, a day after the government increased prices of prime commodities by up to 600 percent and imposed a 15 percent sales tax on all goods. On Thursday, in response to a call by the 2-million-member <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, a general strike closed most businesses and shut down communications and transportation facilities. The government rescinded the price increases on Thursday, but it was not known whether the tax also was eliminated. Officials in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> reported the first apparent loosening of the general strike's grip on the country. <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> International Airport sent a notice to area airports that it was back in business for the first time since late Wednesday. But the national airline <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>' scheduled service to <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> was canceled Friday night because airline employees remained on strike. The diplomat in <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION> said <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> still suffers from a `` complete paralyzation of transport, communications and everyday life. ... The railway is down. Inter - and inner-city buses have stopped rolling Shops are closed.'' It appeared that since the government backed down on the price increases, anger has turned to Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>'s refusal to submit to the government and <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> a tentative agreement to end the country's 5 -LCB- - year-old civil war The head of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unionist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, junior partner in the governing coalition, negotiated the pact with <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Garang </PERSON>, a renegade army colonel who heads the rebels in southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. The agreement called for a cease-fire and suspension of Islamic law in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> until the matter can be discussed in a constitutional conference, a major concession for <PERSON> Garang </PERSON>. He had vowed that his mainly Christian and animist forces would continue to fight until the Islam-based legal code was abrogated. <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> reportedly was concerned that endorsing the Islamic law clause would prompt the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> to leave the government, removing a buffer that the prime minister has used in disputes with the Democratic Unionists. Since the street protests began, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unionists </ORGANIZATION>, who dominate the trade union federation, have quit the government in sympathy. Reports on Friday said <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> has accepted the six <ORGANIZATION> Unionist </ORGANIZATION> ministers' resignations and will name <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Turabi </PERSON>, his brother-in-law and attorney-general, to the key Unionist-held post of foreign minister. That would make <PERSON> Turabi </PERSON> the government's peace negotiator with <PERSON> Garang </PERSON>. As attorney-general <PERSON> Turabi </PERSON> drafted the Islamic legal code, and as head of the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> he has spearheaded opposition to the Unionist-negotiated agreement, so prospects for successfully concluded talks would be virtually nil.
