<HEAD>Protesters Hang Banner on Communist Party Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two opposition activists on Friday hung a protest banner reading `` Free the Politicals'' from a balcony at the headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in the capital. The banner was signed with the initials of the banned <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> regional council of the Solidarity trade union movement. The protest was connected with a weeklong hunger protest taking place in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> through Sunday to draw attention to the detention of anti-military activists in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. Brief displays of opposition banners from public buildings are fairly common in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. However, this appeared to be the first time activists managed to place one on the guarded headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Security workers seized the 15-foot-long banner after about five minutes. The activists, <PERSON> Piotr </PERSON> <PERSON> Ikonowicz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Mizikowski </PERSON>, were led away into the building and detained, according to <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinior </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. Authorities meanwhile freed a secret policeman Friday who was sentenced to prison for helping underground members of Solidarity, prison officials and opposition sources said. <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodysz </PERSON>, 48, was arrested in 1984 and initially charged with cooperating with Solidarity's underground. Authorities later sentenced him to six years in prison on a more serious charge of corruption, alleging he had taken money to pass police secrets to Solidarity. Solidarity activists have denied any financial motive for <PERSON> Hodysz </PERSON>'s cooperation. They say he was motivated by sympathy for the union movement, which authorities crushed in late 1981 and banned in 1982. <PERSON> Hodysz </PERSON>, a former captain in the state <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, was released from a prison in <LOCATION> Koszalin </LOCATION>, in northwestern <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, according to a duty officer at the <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penitentiaries </ORGANIZATION>. The official refused to give his name. The former policeman was eligible for the parole, subject to good behavior, because he had served two-thirds of his prison sentence. After his release, <PERSON> Hodysz </PERSON> went to <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brygida </LOCATION>'s Church in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, a northern port, to meet with Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and the Rev. <PERSON> Henryk </PERSON> <PERSON> Jankowski </PERSON>, according to a <PERSON> Jankowski </PERSON> aide. <PERSON> Jankowski </PERSON> is a <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> adviser. At the time of <PERSON> Hodysz </PERSON>'s arrest, authorities were trying to stamp out any vestige of Solidarity, the first independent labor movement in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. However, they have increasingly tolerated the movement in recent years and even allowed <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> to speak in an uncensored television debate in November.
