<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> suffer from headaches you do n't get from guerrilla infiltrators, hostile Arab neighbors, or even a Palestinian uprising. No, they have some real headaches: the kind that make your temples throb, turn your brain to porridge, and transform a political speech into medieval torture. Lawmakers blame the endemic headaches on their 22-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> building, whose poor ventilation and air conditioning have earned it the nickname `` The Submarine.'' Doctors, in turn, dubbed the lawmakers' physical complaints `` The Submarine Syndrome.'' Parliament Speaker <PERSON> Dov </PERSON> <PERSON> Shilansky </PERSON> said Friday the problem has `` a great influence'' on legislators' ability to function. `` This is not a joke; it is a serious problem. I know a lot of legislators who suffer from headaches and dizziness,'' <PERSON> Shilansky </PERSON> said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> army radio. Asked if this was why many of the 120 legislators often look sleepy, <PERSON> Shilansky </PERSON> said: `` It's really hard to sit here for the whole day. If you spend a whole day here, you leave with a headache.'' The five-story Parliament building on a hilltop in central <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> was inaugurated in 1966. The two lower floors, including parts of the main auditorium, are partly underground. The Submarine Syndrome can do more than give you a pounding headache, said <PERSON> Shilansky </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc. `` When I was a new Knesset -LRB- parliament -RRB- member, I met a man who told me that he was a <ORGANIZATION> Knesset </ORGANIZATION> worker, had a good job, and was happy with it. But he resigned because of poor ventilation. He said a doctor told him: ` You have a choice between shortening your life or resigning,''' he said. <PERSON> Raanan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, a freshman legislator from the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said he has begun to suffer frequent headaches since the 12th <ORGANIZATION> Knesset </ORGANIZATION> opened Nov. 21. `` Normally, I do n't have headaches, and I think there's some problem with the building,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. Throughout the building, it's either too hot or too cold, said maintenance manager <PERSON> Shmaryahu </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckhaus </PERSON>. `` If we heat the first floor where people complain of cold, the heat spreads to the second and third floors, and people there ... feel suffocated by the heat. If we turn down the heat, people on the first floor complain of cold,'' he said. Experts say the solution is to break down the air-conditioning system into smaller systems with individual controls in different parts of the building. But <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> said that answer is too expensive. Parliament doctors advise legislators to walk outside from time to time for a breath of fresh air, the radio said. But legislators can not always heed that advice during long debates that often deteriorate into shouting matches _ especially unbearable to people suffering from headaches.
