<HEAD>Military Court Orders 20 Held in Fishermen's Massacre</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A military court on Friday ordered the arrest of 20 members of a military-police task force implicated in the massacre of 14 Venezuelan fishermen in October. `` There was no armed confrontation, but the loss of 14 innocent lives,'' said Gen. <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Zambrano </PERSON>, who overruled a lower military court decision in November that the task force acted in `` legitimate self-defense.'' <PERSON> Zambrano </PERSON> presided over a War Council, the highest regional military court, in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cristobal </LOCATION>, about 400 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>. He ordered the arrest of the 20 Venezuelans _ 16 members of special police forces and four members of the armed forces _ and a Colombian man believed to be an informant for the brigade. Military spokesmen originally said the 14 men killed were Colombian guerrillas shot in an Oct. 29 firefight with government forces out to prevent them from blowing up oil installations along the Colombian-Venezuelan border. But two survivors who jumped into a river and swam for their lives denied those shot were guerrillas and said they were all fishermen out on a picnic. A major factor in the military's reversal was evidence released publicly, although never made official, that an exhumation of the 14 bodies showed most of the men were shot either in the back or in the head at close range. The case attracted international attention. Government officials received letters from human rights and church groups around the world demanding justice. Townspeople of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Amparo </LOCATION>, near the site of the massacre, backed up the two survivors' claims in interviews with journalists. The two survivors, <PERSON> Wolmer </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinilla </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>, later sought asylum in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> rather than face the military court for trial on charges of `` military rebellion'' based on the official version of events.
