cut-up wreckage to the Royal Aerospace Establishment 300 miles south at <LOCATION> Farnborough </LOCATION>, southwest of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Investigators from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accidents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Branch </ORGANIZATION> will examine it for clues about the bomb. Police roped off an area near the wreckage where relatives of crash victims can place flowers. The Times reported Friday that investigators believe the bomb's first trigger was a barometric device set to go off under a change of altitude This would activate the second trigger, an electronic timer, to make the bomb explode at a later time, it said. Terrorists developed the double detonator technique after some airports started putting cargo through pressure chambers which can detonate pressure-activated bombs, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The investigators have yet to establish whether a suitcase containing the bomb passed through <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>'s pressure chamber, setting off the timing device, or whether the timer was activated in flight,'' the newspaper said. The caller claiming to speak for the Guardians of the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolution </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that unless the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> deports <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON>, son of the late <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, `` there will be another present in the New Year for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The day after the crash, an anonymous caller claimed it was retaliation by the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution for downing of an <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </