<HEAD>Moderate Quake Shakes South Bay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A moderate earthquake shook <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> communities Friday afternoon, but no injuries or damages were reported, authorities said. The earthquake struck at 3:54 p.m. abou 15 miles east of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION> and measured 4.3 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, said <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Jorgenson </PERSON>, of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Geological Survey in <LOCATION> Menlo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. The quake occurred on the <LOCATION> Calaveras </LOCATION> fault and was felt as far north as <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION>, about 15 miles north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION> and 45 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Jorgenson </PERSON>. The <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale is a measure of the energy released by an earthquake, as measured by ground motion recorded on a seismograph. A single increase in magnitude, as in from 5.5 to 6.5, means a tenfold increase of ground motion. A quake of 3.5 can cause slight damage in populated areas, while a quake of 6.0 can cause severe damage. In March 1964 an earthquake in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> hit 8.5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, killing 114 people.
