<HEAD>Artillery Shell With Explosives and Depleted Uranium Misplaced In
Lab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIVERMORE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Part of an artillery shell containing conventional explosives and depleted uranium was accidentally shipped to the <ORGANIZATION> Sandia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>, a newspaper reported Friday. The test shell sat at the lab for four days in August 1987 before it was discovered, said the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jose </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. Depleted uranium is incapable of causing a nuclear explosion and only slightly radioactive, but it is poisonous when inhaled. Officials at <LOCATION> Sandia </LOCATION>'s main facility in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, said the risk of a conventional explosion was very low. `` It did n't pose any danger,'' said <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hey </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Sandia </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, on Friday. `` The thing is we just did n't follow the rules.'' The shell was shipped to the lab as unclassified freight from the <LOCATION> Tonopah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Test </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Range </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, where a clerk mixed it up with another shipment. The shell was to have remained there for a future shipment, where it would have been properly labeled. The wooden crate carrying the device should have been marked as classified package containing explosive and radioactive material, Hey said. It was supposed to be shipped to a secret weapons testing site at the <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Livermore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>. Instead, it was flown to the <LOCATION> Alameda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> by a government contractor and carried to the <ORGANIZATION> Sandia </ORGANIZATION> lab by a <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> truck as a routine delivery. The shell was placed under armed guard after its discovery. `` It caused a lot of concern, and it was taken as an example of how things can go wrong,'' Hey said. Test range officials have since revised shipping rules.
