<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> for the first time Friday suspended payment on its $ 16.5-billion foreign debt for three months, when the government is to obtain a new loan to meet the payments. Treasury Minister <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Alarcon </PERSON>, who announced the decision, said the country's creditors agreed to the suspension. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> was the only Latin American country up to now that had not restructured its debt or suspended its payments. The minister said <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> will receive in April an international loan of $ 1.7 billion that will ensure it will have the funds needed to pay interest and principal on the foreign debt until 1990. The 90-day moratorium means <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> will not pay $ 300 million, which can be used for economic development programs, he told a news conference. The $ 300 million will be paid after <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> receives the additional loan, he said. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> had asked for a $ 1.85 billion loan in negotiations with international bankers to pay its foreign debt. Political leaders and economic analysts had recommended that President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>'s government renegotiate the foreign debt under more favorable terms. In recent years, 40 percent of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s income from exports has been spent to service the debt. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last week approved a law making it easier for the government to renegotiate the debt with its creditors, saying it was impossible to continue paying the debt under the current schedule.
