<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Isamu </PERSON> <PERSON> Noguchi </PERSON>, the renowned American sculptor whose work graces museums, gardens and parks around the world, died Friday after a brief illness. He was 84. <PERSON> Noguchi </PERSON>, whose work blended the esthetics of East and West, was best known for monumental public sculpture but also designed furniture and lamps, stage sets, gardens, fountains, playgrounds and worked in several artistic media. He received the National Medal of Arts from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> at the White House in June 1987. `` He was one of the most important artists of the 20th century,'' said <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, associate director of the <ORGANIZATION> Whitney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION>. `` His career had an extraordinary range.'' Among his works are the gleaming steel <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fountain </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, a 28-foot red cube that stands on one of its corners in front of a lower <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> bank and the Sunken Garden at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Chase </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plaza </LOCATION> He also designed the <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> garden in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, the Billy Rose Sculpture Garden in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> and two bridges for <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION>'s Peace Park. <PERSON> Noguchi </PERSON> worked in many materials including wood, bronze and galvanized steel, but his major sculptures are made of stone: basalt, granite and marble. He is represented in the permanent collections of such major American museums as the Metropolitan, <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> and Modern in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has lost its greatest living sculptor,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wardwell </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Isamu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Noguchi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Garden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>. `` Of course he was much more than a sculptor _ he was a designer of spaces, stage sets, gardens, fountains and the decorative arts. He was a great thinker and visionary.'' `` Art was it. He wrote a lot, but it was about art,'' <PERSON> Wardwell </PERSON> said. `` He was very much an innovator and not a follower,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>. <PERSON> Noguchi </PERSON> once said he was `` suspicious of the whole business of style _ again it is a form of inhibition.'' <ORGANIZATION> Wardwell </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Noguchi </PERSON> died at <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at 2 a.m. Friday of heart failure. At the time of his death, he had just returned from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and was working on several large marble sculptures among other projects, including the Bayfront Park in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, a memorial to the Challenger astronauts. He had just been commissioned to do a major park for the city of <LOCATION> Sapporo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Noguchi </PERSON> lived in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> but spent much time in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, including his formative years, and he employed numerous artisans at a large workshop in Takamatsu on the Japanese island of <ORGANIZATION> Shikoku </ORGANIZATION>. The son of a Japanese poet and an American writer, he was born in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> on Nov. 17, 1904, but two years later his family took him to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. He returned alone to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1918 and went to school in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Noguchi </PERSON> entered <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> as a pre-medical student in 1922, but dropped out in favor of sculpture studies at the <ORGANIZATION> Leonardo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Da </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vinci </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, now defunct. He moved to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in 1928 and became a studio assistant for <PERSON> Constantin </PERSON> <PERSON> Brancusi </PERSON> for six months. During that time, his earliest works were made. <PERSON> Noguchi </PERSON> returned to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1929 and had his first one-man show at the <ORGANIZATION> Eugene </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schoen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gallery </ORGANIZATION>. He survived on the sales of a few bronze head portraits and on grants, including a Guggenheim fellowship in 1927, which enabled him to travel to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, where he studied drawing, ink-brush painting and pottery. One of his first competitive successes was a 1938 commission for the 10-ton, stainless-steel relief above the entrance to The Associated Press Building at Rockefeller Center. The piece, one of his few representational pieces, depicts five journalists at work. His sculptures were often smooth-surfaced vaguely biological forms that remind some scholars of the surrealistic paintings of <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Miro </PERSON> and of primitive Japanese `` haniwa'' figures. In later years his work became more geometric, while retaining organic imagery. The naturalistic style was once described in The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> as `` a restrained vocabulary of organic forms ranging from playful biomorphs and abstract figures to subtle mounds, polished rings and massive boulders.'' He said he was fascinated by `` abandoned stones'' that `` allow me to enter into their life's purpose.'' His works are found outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Modern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION>, the Art Gallery of <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, the Rijksmuseum Kroller-Muller in <LOCATION> Otterlo </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Ulster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Bayerische </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vereinsbank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Noguchi </PERSON> had an active social life, but lived modestly in a small apartment. He was married briefly to the Japanese actress <PERSON> Yoshiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamaguchi </PERSON> but they were separated by immigration difficulties and later divorced. They had no children. He is survived by a sister, <PERSON> Ailes </PERSON> <PERSON> Spinden </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION>, N.M. There will be a memorial service at the Noguchi Garden Museum Feb. 7, but the funeral and burial services will be private, <ORGANIZATION> Wardwell </ORGANIZATION> said.
