<HEAD>Unbundled Stock Unit Backers Change Marketing Strategy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The inventors of the unbundled stock unit are confident they can tie up enough loose ends for still-unconvinced investors to make February's planned offering of the new security a success. But the developers who initially pitched the securities as a way to unlock hidden values in a company by breaking a share of its stock into three tradable components are now emphasizing the value of the three pieces as a package. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallatin </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> executive who oversaw the development of the unbundled stock unit, insists the new marketing approach simply reflects an effort to point out what may have been an underappreciated reason for making the switch from common stock to unbundled stock unit. `` There seems to be no question that long before the important date, there will be more than enough people comfortable with it'' to proceed with the offerings, he said. The important date may be in early February after the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> completes its review of the proposal and the offerings begin. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> and four clients _ <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pfizer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sara </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ said Dec. 5 that they planned to offer shareholders a chance to exchange about $ 5.6 billion in common stock for unbundled stock units. The precise exchange ratio has not been announced, and some investors are pushing to get one unbundled unit for slightly less than a share of common. The unbundled stock unit consists of a 30-year bond paying interest equal to the company's current dividend, a preferred stock that will reflect any increase in the dividend and an equity appreciation certificate that will reflect stock price appreciation in excess of the bond's stated value. It is expected that each of the units will trade separately on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> along with the company's common stock and a unit that will combine the preferred stock and equity appreciation certificate. The stock exchange recently made a proposal to the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> that would allow the issuance of unbundled stock units with certain restrictions. The restrictions include limiting the total outstanding stock that can be converted into unbundled units to no more than 25 percent. In addition, the voting rights of the remaining stockholders should not be adversely affected by an exchange of stock for unbundled units and individual shareholders should be allowed to swap their shares without a shareholder vote. <PERSON> Gallatin </PERSON> said his firm has no objection to the exchange's recommendations, and noted that each of the four offerings proposed to date are in compliance <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> has been briefing institutional investors who are being counted on to be major participants in the market for unbundled stock units. Among the reservations that some investors have expressed are that the exchange will be taxable and that unbundled units carry no voting rights. Some have also questioned how liquid the market for the new securities will be and have found it difficult to place a value on the preferred and equity appreciation components of the unbundled unit. <LOCATION> Gallatin </LOCATION> said the taxability issue should not pose a problem for tax-exempt investors such as pension funds and may be an incentive for investors who may have a capital loss rather than a gain. Voting rights would be restored in the event of a takeover. In addition, <PERSON> Gallatin </PERSON> said those trying to place a value on the various pieces of the unbundled stock unit should consider the extras in the package as a whole. While companies can cut dividends, they are less likely to skip an interest payment and that is what the dividend becomes after the share of stock is traded for the unbundled stock unit. The bond has a face value after 30 years of about 2.5 times the current stock price with the potential for even more with the equity appreciation certificate. In an analysis of the Pfizer offering, the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its experts `` have guardedly assigned a value of about 5-10 percent of the price of the common to these new guarantees which might be realized if one were to hold the pieces for 30 years.'' But they added that if investors do not consider the value of these provisions `` attractive enough to offset the lack of common voting rights and the potential liquidity problem, the offering may be untenable.'' Some investors want to wait until the new securities are in the market. In a recent report for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, analysts <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Metz </PERSON> said `` the jury is still out on the probable success'' of the new securities and described initial reaction as mixed But they added, `` Were the reaction of market participants to remain favorable, the incentive would be strong for other companies to adopt the proposal.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday Jan. 2</NOTE>
