 Ind </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> said it took nearly three years to get the movie made after the project was dropped by <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, then picked up by <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>. `` That's a long time to care about a movie,'' she said. `` But more important, I was concerned about <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>. His health went up and down. I wanted to get it done so he could be a part of it. `` Many people called about the rights to <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>'s story. But nobody went to <LOCATION> Kokomo </LOCATION> and said, ` I want to make this movie,' except me. They did n't say yes right away. I sent them tapes of ` Adam' and ` Bill','' two other real-life movies she has produced. <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>'s story was filmed in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, the third movie <PERSON> Otto </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Landsburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, has made there The others were `` A Stoning in <LOCATION> Fulham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'' for <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and `` Quiet Victory: The Charlie Wedemeyer Story'' for CBS. <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> is now awaiting word from <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> on another picture to be filmed there, `` Unspeakable Acts,'' about a child abuse case in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Otto </PERSON>'s movie `` Adam'' was about the murder-kidnaping of <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, which caused his father to crusade for a law setting up a national clearinghouse for missing children, and `` Bill'' was about a mentally retarded man, played by <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Rooney </PERSON>, who was able to make it on his own.
