<FIRST>r f PM-CoorsLabels Bjt   12-30 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coors Labels, Bjt,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coors Brings Back Old Label To Appease Disgruntled Beer Drinkers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE WHEELAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Adolph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has learned what happens when you change the label of the flagship beer but do n't change the ingredients: some beer drinkers are convinced it just does n't taste the same. Last summer, <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> put a new `` Original Draft'' label on its flagship beer to attract younger drinkers and compete with <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s successful draft beer advertising campaign. But some beer drinkers in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> _ two <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> loyalist strongholds _ thought the retirement of the old `` Banquet Beer'' label meant the beer had changed, although it had n't. Sales fell in some liquor stores and taverns as cans and bottles bearing the old `` Banquet Beer'' label gave way to `` Original Draft.'' `` We thought the change would help us, but it kind of backfired,'' <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Distributing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION> said Thursday. `` We were talking to the brewery to try to tell them how much it was hurting us.'' Coors, battling for a bigger share of the beer market, paid attention. Next week, <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION>, will begin selling the beer under the old `` Banquet Beer'' label again in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> _ alongside its `` Original Draft'' label. The Coors experience in some ways recalls <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s experiment in April 1985, when it replaced its original cola flavor with a new formulation The ensuing consumer protest forced Coca-Cola to bring back the old flavor three months later, renaming it `` Coca-Cola Classic.'' `` We were faced with a choice _ argue with the customers and say it is the same beer, or give them what they wanted,'' <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Albee </PERSON> said from company headquarters in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> suburb. Coors introduced the `` Original Draft'' label because <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was having success with an advertising campaign that emphasized its draft beer, <PERSON> Albee </PERSON> said. He said <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> wanted consumers to know <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> has been putting draft beer in bottles since 1959. `` We also found that new graphics could attract perhaps a younger drinker, in the 21 to 25 age group,'' he said. The brewery began bottling the beer under the new label last July. This fall, <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> officials were surprised to learn they had some disgruntled customers. `` We found there was confusion about whether it was a different beer,'' said <PERSON> Albee </PERSON>. `` We never in our advertising campaign said this is the same beer in a new package. Perhaps that added to the confusion.'' <PERSON> Albee </PERSON> said <PERSON> Coors </PERSON> asked the company's 600 beer distributors whether they wanted the old label back. `` The only response was in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>. About 20 said they would take Banquet.'' <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> has a loyal following in those areas, said <PERSON> Albee </PERSON>, who thinks the label change was more readily accepted in areas where <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> has not been available so long. The beer has been sold in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> since 1937, and in southwest <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> since 1948. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said that in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, the label change was especially unpopular with Hispanics over 40, who form the core of El Paso Coors drinkers. <PERSON> Albee </PERSON> said it will not cost the brewery extra to put two kinds of labels on its bottles and cans. `` After running out a few thousand cases, you break about even,'' he said. He thinks that while <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> lost some business with the label change in a few locations, the `` Original Draft'' label already is building a following that could increase sales. And Coors does not plan to change its advertising campaign because of diehard `` Banquet Beer'' label fans. `` Ninety-some-odd percent of our business is Original Draft -LRB- labels -RRB- and will continue to be,'' said <PERSON> Albee </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
