<HEAD>Judge Restrains Takeover Effort, Cites Drexel Case As One Reason</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge's decision stalling a $ 970 million takeover effort is based on concerns about the deal's huge debt financing and criminal sanctions hanging over its investment banker, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The order by U.S. District Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON> late Thursday came hours before <ORGANIZATION> MAI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Basic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Four </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 20-a-share bid for <ORGANIZATION> Prime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> was due to expire. MAI Basic extended the bid until Jan. 11. <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON>'s ruling appeared to be the first time that concern over <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s record settlement of securities fraud charges announced last week had affected litigation in a hostile takeover fight. <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON> said he wanted more information from <LOCATION> Tustin </LOCATION>, Calif.-based MAI Basic, which is about one fourth the size of Prime, involving `` the ambitious, fragile and possibly illegal financial requirements through which -LRB- it and other investors -RRB- propose to acquire Prime.'' The judge said MAI Basic, controlled by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> financier <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> LeBow </PERSON>, and its investment banker <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, are proposing a deal that will cost a total of $ 1.5 billion with `` virtually all of this financing -LRB- taking -RRB- the form of debt.'' Of the $ 1.5 billion, $ 875 million would be in the form of junk bond financing from <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, which <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON> noted has `` acknowledged its guilt to six felony counts related to its involvement in similarly heavily leveraged transactions.'' `` Suggestions that <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s guilty plea improves its financial stability, while not necessarily disingenuous, are not helpful,'' <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON> said. Prime stock closed at $ 17.75, up 37.5 cents, in composite <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading Thursday. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Eluck </PERSON>, an attorney for MAI Basic, said he was optimistic MAI Basic would address some of <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON>'s concerns about financial disclosures and that MAI Basic would be able to satisfy his latest concerns. The judge also said MAI Basic's offer requires the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> courts to strike down Prime's `` poison pill'' anti-takeover plan or for Prime's board to rescind it, which is unlikely. Prime is headquartered in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> but incorporated in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>. `` The bidders acknowledge that the poison pill makes Prime prohibitively expensive,'' <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON> said. `` Yet, despite a <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> court decision refusing to enjoin the plan, the bidders continue to assert with confidence that they can consummate the deal.'' <PERSON> Eluck </PERSON> said MAI Basic intended to pursue efforts in the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> courts aimed at overturning Prime's poison pill. Under the plan, if a party acquires more than 20 percent of Prime, current shareholders are entitled to buy shares at half price. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Eluck </PERSON> said MAI Basic would respond promptly to <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON>'s latest queries for further details of the financing. `` We think we will be able to provide them and comply with the judge's directions for further disclosures by the end of next week,'' he said. Prime said in a statement: `` We are gratified by the district court's order and its recognition of the serious economic and legal questions raised by MAI's efforts to acquire Prime.''
