<HEAD>A Volatile Year For Interest Rates</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The interest rate forecast for 1988 turned out to be a bit like a long-range weather report, with few experts accurately predicting what was in store for the borrowing public. `` Everyone was thrown for a loop,'' said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldinger </PERSON>, a principal of the <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, investment banking firm <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` It was a year that frustrated many.'' Consumers and businesses generally saw short-term interest rates soar while longer-term rates were little changed from the previous year, a mixed blessing for both groups. As a result, the so-called yield curve, which illustrates the difference between short - and long rates in the bond market, took an unusual turn in 1988 First it flattened from the normal upward slope, then started to invert for the first time in about six years. `` I think if you were to try to isolate one key factor of the 1988 fixed-income environment it was the pronounced flattening of the yield curve,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, director of money-market research for <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. On the last day of trading in 1988, for instance, the yield on the one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill was slightly higher than that of the bellwether 30-year bond, 9.00 percent vs. 8.98 percent The 3-month-bill yield was still 0.64 percentage points lower than the long bond, although normally the gap is around 2 percentage points. Long-term rates usually are significantly higher to compensate investors for their increased risk. -LRB- For instance, it's more likely that someone will renege on a 30-year debt than on one lasting three months. -RRB- The last time the yield curve inverted, the stock market took a tumble and the nation headed into a recession. Few economists, though, are predicting a similar scenario for 1989. In fact, it was fears of the opposite occurring that pushed short-term rates as high as they are now. `` The short-end rise -LRB- in rates -RRB- came from the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> tightening,'' said <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>. At the start of 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> eased its credit policies by keeping interest rates down, out of near-universal concern the country was close to a recession from the previous October's stock market crash. But the economy showed surprising resilience. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> then started to worry about rising inflation, along with an unstable dollar in foreign exchange, and switched gears by tightening credit. Inflation actually remained in check throughout the year, which is partly why long-term interest rates and prices remained fairly stable, economists said. The central bank took its biggest inflation-fighting stand in August, when it raised the discount rate, the interest charged on loans to member banks, a half percentage point to 6.5 percent. Other indirect movements have been made known since. Commercial lending rates followed suit. Major banks lowered their prime lending rates _ used to set rates on most corporate and consumer loans _ a quarter of a percentage point to 8.5 percent on Feb. 2, then raised them a half percentage point four times to 10.5 percent by year's end. There was a similar pattern for mortgage rates. For a conventional 30-year fixed-rate mortgage, rates ranged from a low of 9.84 percent in mid-February to a high of 10.77 percent at year's end, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION> The interest rate climate did n't have too much effect on the volume of municipal and corporate issues. For the year, the volume of municipal issues totaled around $ 112 billion, compared with $ 101.5 billion in 1987. The volume of corporate issues rose to around $ 275 billion from $ 272.19 billion. Many economists predict that rates will continue to rise during the first half of 1989, with the 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond yielding as much as 9.5 percent. It was as low as 8.29 percent in February and as high as 9.45 in August. During the second half, interest rates should decline as the economy starts to cool down, economists predict. `` We expect <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> policy next year to be driven primarily by inflation and inflation expectations,'' said <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Jenrette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 31-Jan. 1</NOTE>
