<HEAD>Soybeans End Year With A Surge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Soybean futures prices surged to a 10-week high Friday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid forecasts of drier weather in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soybean belt and rumors of more soybean meal purchases by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. On other markets, energy futures rose sharply; precious metals were higher; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and stock-index futures retreated. Volume was uniformly light in thin trading conditions with many traders away for the holidays. Most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> futures markets closed at noon local time and will not reopen until Tuesday morning. Soybeans settled 7 \ cents to 17 cents higher with the contract for delivery in January at $ 8.04 -RCB- a bushel, marking the first settlement above $ 8 for a near-month soybean contract since Oct. 19 Some meteorologists said a high-pressure ridge was forming over the central section of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, which could cause a return to the unusually warm, dry conditions that marked the recent soybean planting period in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. Additional buying was prompted by rumors that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> planned to buy more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soybean meal, said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. A Soviet purchase of at least 600,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soybean meal earlier this week surprised traders and boosted optimism about export sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grains. `` The Soviets are on a very aggressive import program for both grain and protein in an attempt to improve food supply and availabilities,'' <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON> said. Grain futures also closed higher. The wheat market was supported by a new 90-day forecast for continued dry weather in the <LOCATION> central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, where winter wheat is grown, <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON> said. Corn was buoyed by spillover buying from the adjacent wheat and soybean pits, he said. Wheat settled 1 -LCB- cents to 3 \ cents higher with March at $ 4.40 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2 -LCB- cents higher with March at $ 2.84 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 2 -LCB- cents to 4 \ cents higher with March at $ 2.43 -RCB- a Crude oil for February delivery steamed through psychological resistance at $ 17 a barrel and soared all the way to $ 17.30 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> before late profit-taking cut the gains. `` When it got past $ 17.15, a cold sweat gripped the shorts -LRB- players who had bet that prices would fall -RRB- and they started to buy,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It was a real buying frenzy in there.'' The rally was almost entirely due to chart signals rather than supply-and-demand factors, he said. But with <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s new oil-production restraints scheduled to take effect Jan. 1, few players were willing to go home holding short positions, he said. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents to 47 cents higher with February at $ 17.24 a barrel; heating oil settled .50 cent to .84 cent higher with January at 53.48 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .77 cent to 1.05 cents higher with January at 47.88 cents a gallon. Gold and silver futures rose modestly on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange in a technical rebound after declining in each of the three previous sessions. Platinum futures advanced slightly on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, but analysts were not encouraged by the rise in prices. `` Going into the new year, I've got to say the trend is a bit down,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, a vice president of precious metals and foreign exchange trading with <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION>. Gold settled $ 1.80 higher across the board with February at $ 412.30 a troy ounce; silver was 3.5 cents to 4 cents higher with March at $ 6.13 a troy ounce; platinum was 80 cents to $ 2.30 higher with January at $ 516.60 a troy ounce. Livestock and meat futures finished narrowly mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in thin, directionless holiday trading. Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .15 cent higher with February at 73.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .07 cent higher with January at 84.15 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent lower to .03 cent higher with February at 46.52 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .07 cent lower to .55 cent higher with February at 43.05 cents a pound. Stock-index futures retreated on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the contract for March delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 index settled 1.70 points lower at 280.40. Each point is w