<NOTE>For Release Monday Jan. 2</NOTE>
<HEAD>Small Investors' Portfolios Gained 10 Percent In 1988, Magazine
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite predictions of gloom following the stock market crash of October 1987, Money magazine's small investor index recorded a 10 percent gain in 1988, the magazine says. The gain raised the value of the typical household's portfolio from $ 70,956 to $ 78,019, the magazine said. The magazine's index is based on figures on individual investment supplied by many sources, including the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, various investment houses and newsletters that follow the investment field. Its household figure is derived by dividing the total amount of individual investment by the number of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> households, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sivy </PERSON>, a Money senior editor. The biggest winners of the year were stocks, especially blue-chip issues, which racked up gains of 17.9 percent in the index, the magazine said. Municipal bonds recorded an 11.4 percent gain for the year, it said. Low short-term rates at the beginning of 1988 made money-market funds and certificates of deposit poor performers, returning 6 percent and 8 percent for the year respectively, it said. Gold was the year's big loser, down in value 26.6 percent, it said. But the metal represents less than 1 percent of individuals' overall investments, it added
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Jan. 2</NOTE>
