<HEAD>Stocks Finish Mixed as Blue-Chips Falter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Blue-chip issues stumbled Friday in their bid to finish 1988 at the highest levels since the October 1987 crash, fading steadily in the afternoon as the overall market posted a mixed finale to a year in which many indicators posted double-digit gains. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 20 points in the previous two sessions to within a point of its highest closing level since the market crash more than 14 months ago, lost 14.11 points to close at 2,168.57. That left the market's best-known barometer with a decline of 0.36 for the week, but with a gain of 229.74 points, or 11.85 percent, for the year. It was also the first year that the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average has finished above the 2,000 mark. Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 3 to 2 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 945 up, 594 down and 466 unchanged. Volume on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> came to 127.21 million shares, down from 131.29 million in the previous session. Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 160.65 million shares. As the session got underway, the Dow Jones industrials moved above the year's closing peak of 2,183.50 set on Oct. 21. But the index turned lower by midmorning, holding at a slightly lower level until midafternoon when it began a steady erosion toward the close. Analysts cited profit-taking in advance of the three-day New Years holiday weekend, program selling by professional traders, a rise in oil prices and weakness in the dollar for the stock market's performance `` It's the end of the year, and the last opportunity to sell,'' said ack <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, a market technician for <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> also pointed out that the market had recovered more ground than many people would have expected at the time of the October 1987 market crash. `` All in all, how bad was 1988? It was an up year and if you scratched anybody during the year, they would have said it was going down,'' he said. The market appeared to shrug off a pair of reports that indicated a slowing economy. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that its Index of Leading Indicators fell 0.2 percent in November, but also revised upward its estimate of the October gain in the leading indicators to a 0.4 percent rise rather than the 0.1 percent increase originally reported. In a separate report, it said sales of new homes fell by 8 percent in November, the largest setback in 18 months. Quantum Chemicals was the most actively-traded issues on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, falling 1 ~ to 105 -RRB- The company's stock climbed 18 -RCB- in the previous two sessions after announcing a recpaitalization plan that included a special dividend. <ORGANIZATION> Anacomp </ORGANIZATION> was the second most active issue and was the biggest percentage loser as it fell 1 \ to 6 -RCB- The company announced lower earnings from operations for its fourth fiscal quarter. <ORGANIZATION> Reebok </ORGANIZATION> rose -RCB- to 12 \ as takeover rumors circulated The automobile stocks fell. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> was fell 1 -RCB- to 83 -LCB-, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> lost 1 to 50 -LCB- and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> fell -RCB- to 25 -RCB-. As measured by <ORGANIZATION> Wilshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>' index of more than 5,000 actively traded stocks, the market fell $ 7.144 billion, or 0.26 percent, in value. For the year, the <LOCATION> Wilshire </LOCATION> index rose $ 318 billion, or 13.1 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index of all its listed common stocks fell 0.64 to 156.26 but finished the week with a 0.20 gain and was up 13 percent from 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's industrial index fell 2.12 to 321.26, and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P's 500-stock composite index lost 1.68 to 277.72 The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose 2.33 to 381.38. At the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the market value index closed at 306.01, up 2.32.
