tors had not considered getting the best price for their stockholders. <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON> also contended that the Holly's board was influenced by managers who are unfriendly to <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON>'s. Industry analysts have said a <ORGANIZATION> Tyson </ORGANIZATION> takeover of <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> would likely lead to management changes at <LOCATION> Holly </LOCATION>, while a merger with <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION> probably would not cause such turnover. `` Apparently, we won the case,'' <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> said from <LOCATION> Tyson </LOCATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Springdale </LOCATION>. `` We are now going to actively pursue the acquisition. It means the playing field has been made into an even ground.'' Officials for <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION> were in meetings and were n't immediately available for comment Earlier Friday, <ORGANIZATION> Tyson </ORGANIZATION> extended its tender offer until Jan. 6. Nearly 3 million of <ORGANIZATION> Holly </ORGANIZATION>'s approximately 20 million shares outstanding had been tendered, <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON> produces more than 2 billion pounds of poultry a year, <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION> turns out about 1.5 billion pounds, and <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Farms </PERSON> processes about 1.2 billion pounds. The court announcement came after the conclusion of nationwide stock trading. Holly stock closed Friday at $ 55.62 -LCB- per share, up 37 -LCB- cents. Tyson closed at $ 17.25, up 37 -LCB- cents. <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION> closed down 12 -LCB- cents, at $ 29.
