<FIRST>u f AM-Zenith-Dumping     12-30 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zenith-Dumping,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zenith Asks U.S. To Monitor TV Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> asked the government Friday to invoke a never-used law to monitor imports of televisions made by companies suspected of `` dumping'' in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> sets they assembled outside their home countries. <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>, the only remaining U.S.-owned TV maker, said monitoring by the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> would discourage foreign TV makers from evading penalties imposed for selling their products in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at unfairly low prices. The request stems from a provision in the 1984 trade law that permits the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to develop a 12-month monitoring program in certain cases. `` We're simply asking the government to enforce the laws on the books,'' <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearlman </PERSON> said in a statement. <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Claire </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchan </PERSON> said in a telephone interview that before going ahead with a monitoring program, the agency would have to find an `` extraordinary pattern of persistent, injurious dumping'' that was causing a serious problem for the domestic industry. She said the department also would have to decide how to monitor imports _ a procedure presumably less complex than a full-scale dumping investigation. `` Because it's a statute that's never been applied, it's something we'll have to look at to determine what is the best way,'' Ms. <PERSON> Buchan </PERSON> said Dumping refers to the sale of products in foreign markets at unfairly low prices to get rid of excess production or to force competitors out of business. <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>, based in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Glenview </LOCATION>, has not had an annual profit since 1984, largely because of fierce competition from cheap imports. <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s 378-page request asks the government to monitor imports of color TVs, picture tubes and parts from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. Those countries have assembly plants established by television manufacturers based in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> claims that by assembling television sets in other countries for export to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the large Asian television makers are evading anti-dumping duties imposed by the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> that raise the prices of Japanese, South Korean and Taiwanese-made sets at their borders. `` Even though a television produced at a <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> plant may have a Japanese picture tube and Japanese chassis and essentially is a Japanese TV set, it's imported into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> without any anti-dumping duties assessed,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>. Anti-dumping provisions for picture tubes also are in place against <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. Ordinarily, a dumping investigation is initiated when a company or industry petitions the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> _ a cumbersome and costly process. But the 1974 trade law also contains a provision for the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to initiate its own investigation if it determines through monitoring that dumping is taking place. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> hopes the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will `` self-initiate'' an investigation in the latest case.
