<HEAD>Energy Futures Close Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crude oil prices broke through the psychologically important $ 17-a-barrel level in a yearend buying spree. Analysts attributed Friday's rally to optimism that the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> would adhere to its new production quotas starting Jan. 1. The 13-nation cartel agreed in November to slash daily production to 18.5 million barrels to help prop up sagging worldwide oil prices. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Friday, the February contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, rose 43 cents to settle at $ 17.24 a barrel, after losing 20 cents on Thursday. Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange Friday, the January contract for wholesale home heating oil rose 0.71 cent to 53.48 cents a gallon. The contract declined 0.72 cent on Thursday. January wholesale unleaded gasoline, which lost 0.03 cent Thursday, closed at 47.88 cents a gallon, up 0.87 cent.
