<FIRST>d f PM-EconomyRdp     12-30 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Indicators Portend Economic Slowdown; Home Sales Skid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The government's chief economic forecasting gauge edged down 0.2 percent in November, continuing a see-saw pattern that analysts said portends a slowdown but no recession in 1989. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report Friday on its Index of Leading Economic Indicators was viewed as good news by some experts, who said it should ease fears that the economy was growing at a pace that threatened new inflation. The 0.2 percent November decline was the fourth drop in the past seven months. Since May, the index has alternated between gains and declines, showing very little forward momentum and suggesting overall economic growth will slow significantly in 1989. In another signal of slower growth, the government reported Friday that sales of new homes fell by 8 percent in November, the biggest decline in 18 months. Analysts blamed the setback on rising mortgage rates likely to further dampen sales in 1989. The last government numbers of 1988 had little or no influence over the financial markets, which closed out the final trading day of the year with mixed results in light trading. Bond prices rose slightly, the dollar weakened marginally against key currencies and the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average fell 14.11 points to close at 2,168.57, though advancing issues slightly outnumbered declines on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration said the setback in the leading index was nothing to become alarmed over, showing only that the economy was slowing a bit. The traditional signal for a recession in the past has been at least three consecutive monthly declines in the index. Private analysts agreed, forecasting that overall economic growth, as measured by the gross national product, will probably dip to around 2.5 percent in 1989. That would be down from an expected growth rate of 3.9 percent in 1988, the economy's best performance in four years.
</TEXT>
